# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: sign-language
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:sign-language/1964-new-york-world-s-fair-p01] The **1964 New York World's Fair** (also known as the **1964–1965 New York World's Fair**) was an international exposition at Flushing Meadows–Corona Park in Queens, New York City, United States.
[src:sign-language/1964-new-york-world-s-fair-p01] The fair included exhibitions, activities, performances, films, art, and food presented by 80 nations, 24 U.S. states, and nearly 350 American companies.
[src:sign-language/1964-new-york-world-s-fair-p01] The five sections of the 646-acre (261 ha) fairground were the Federal and State, International, Transportation, Lake Amusement, and Industrial areas.
[src:sign-language/1964-new-york-world-s-fair-p01] The fair's theme was "Peace through Understanding", and its symbol was the Unisphere, a stainless-steel model of Earth.
[src:sign-language/1964-new-york-world-s-fair-p01] Initially, the fair had 139 pavilions, and 34 concessions and shows.
[src:sign-language/1964-new-york-world-s-fair-p01] The site had previously hosted the 1939 New York World's Fair.
[src:sign-language/1964-new-york-world-s-fair-p01] In the 1950s, several businessmen devised plans for a similar event in 1964, and the New York World's Fair 1964 Corporation (WFC) was formed in 1959.
[src:sign-language/1964-new-york-world-s-fair-p01] Eisenhower approved the fair, the Bureau International des Expositions refused to grant it formal recognition.
[src:sign-language/1964-new-york-world-s-fair-p01] Construction began in late 1960, and over 100 exhibitors signed up for the fair over the next three years.
[src:sign-language/1964-new-york-world-s-fair-p01] The fair ran for two six-month seasons from April 22 to October 18, 1964, and from April 21 to October 17, 1965.
[src:sign-language/1964-new-york-world-s-fair-p01] Despite initial projections of 70 million visitors, just over 51.6 million attended.
[src:sign-language/1964-new-york-world-s-fair-p01] After the fair closed, some pavilions were preserved or relocated, but most of the structures were demolished.
[src:sign-language/1964-new-york-world-s-fair-p01] The fair showcased mid-20th-century American culture and technology.
[src:sign-language/1964-new-york-world-s-fair-p01] The sections were designed in various architectural styles.
[src:sign-language/1964-new-york-world-s-fair-p01] Anyone could host an exhibit if they could afford to rent the land and pay for a pavilion.
[src:sign-language/1964-new-york-world-s-fair-p01] There were several amusement and transport rides, various plazas and fountains, and at its peak, 198 restaurants that served dishes such as Belgian waffles, some of which were popularized by the fair.
[src:sign-language/1964-new-york-world-s-fair-p01] There were more than 30 entertainment events, 40 theaters, and various music performances.
[src:sign-language/1964-new-york-world-s-fair-p01] Exhibitors displayed sculptures, visual art and artifacts, and consumer products such as electronics and cars.
[src:sign-language/1964-new-york-world-s-fair-p01] The contemporaneous press criticized the event as a financial failure, although it influenced 21st-century technologies, and popularized consumer products such as the Ford Mustang.
[src:sign-language/1964-new-york-world-s-fair-p01] Before European settlement of the area, the site of the 1964 World's Fair, Flushing Meadows–Corona Park in Queens, New York City, was a natural wetland straddling the Flushing River.
[src:sign-language/1964-new-york-world-s-fair-p01] In the early 20th century, the site was occupied by the Corona Ash Dumps, before it was selected as the site of the 1939–1940 World's Fair.
[src:sign-language/1964-new-york-world-s-fair-p01] The theme of the 1939–1940 was "the world of tomorrow"; the event was unprofitable, recouping only 32% of its original cost.
[src:sign-language/1964-new-york-world-s-fair-p01] After the 1939 fair, the site was used as a park, but fell into disrepair due to a lack of funds.
[src:sign-language/1964-new-york-world-s-fair-p01] The development of the 1964 fair coincided with social upheavals of the early 1960s, including the civil rights movement, Vietnam War protests, and the aftermath of U.S.
[src:sign-language/1964-new-york-world-s-fair-p01] The idea for the 1964 fair was conceived by a group of businessmen.
[src:sign-language/1964-new-york-world-s-fair-p01] Among them was Robert Kopple, a lawyer who first discussed the idea at a family dinner in 1958 before suggesting it at a meeting of the Mutual Admiration Society the following year.
[src:sign-language/1964-new-york-world-s-fair-p01] The year 1964 was nominally selected to coincide with the 300th anniversary of the British conquest of the Dutch colony of New Netherland.
[src:sign-language/1964-new-york-world-s-fair-p01] Kopple and two friends, Charles Preusse and Thomas J.
[src:sign-language/1964-new-york-world-s-fair-p01] Deegan, met with 35 potential financiers at the 21 Club restaurant.
[src:sign-language/1964-new-york-world-s-fair-p01] Wagner Jr. and parks commissioner Robert Moses formally endorsed the proposal in August 1959, and 75 businessmen formed the New York World's Fair 1964 Corporation (WFC) that month.
[src:sign-language/1964-new-york-world-s-fair-p01] Moses, who saw a 1964 fair as a means to develop the Flushing Meadows site, offered to let the WFC use Flushing Meadows for a nominal fee.
[src:sign-language/1964-new-york-world-s-fair-p01] The fairground would include the 1939 World's Fair site and a part of the nearby Kissena Corridor Park.
[src:sign-language/1964-new-york-world-s-fair-p01] The bid required approval from the United States Congress and the Bureau International des Expositions (BIE), the French organization that was in charge of approving world's fairs.
[src:sign-language/1964-new-york-world-s-fair-p01] Los Angeles and Washington, D.C., were submitting competing bids, so in October 1959, U.S. president Dwight D.
[src:sign-language/1964-new-york-world-s-fair-p01] Eisenhower appointed a committee to review the 1964 world's fair bids, and he approved the New York bid later that month.
[src:sign-language/1964-new-york-world-s-fair-p01] By late 1959, 75 nations had informally indicated an intention to attend the fair, and the WFC began looking for a president and three additional managers in early 1960.
[src:sign-language/1964-new-york-world-s-fair-p01] Moses was tentatively selected as the WFC's president that March, despite Kopple's objections that Moses was too old.
[src:sign-language/1964-new-york-world-s-fair-p01] In turn, Moses would not take the job unless Kopple resigned, as the two men had disagreed bitterly over the canceled Mid-Manhattan Elevated Expressway.
[src:sign-language/1964-new-york-world-s-fair-p01] After Kopple quit the WFC, Moses formally became the WFC's president that May.
[src:sign-language/1964-new-york-world-s-fair-p01] Moses wanted the fair to run for two years, and consultants for the WFC predicted the fair would have 70 million visitors during that time.
[src:sign-language/1964-new-york-world-s-fair-p01] Moses traveled to Paris to ask for the BIE's recognition of the fair.
[src:sign-language/1964-new-york-world-s-fair-p01] The BIE allowed the WFC to begin planning the fair in November 1959, but its officials decided to not formally recognize the fair.
[src:sign-language/1964-new-york-world-s-fair-p01] Under BIE rules, world's fairs could run for only one six-month period, though the WFC had tried to request an exemption.
[src:sign-language/1964-new-york-world-s-fair-p01] The New York fair would also charge rent to foreign governments, contravening another BIE rule that prevented rent from being charged to exhibitors.
[src:sign-language/1964-new-york-world-s-fair-p01] In addition, the BIE allowed only one exposition per country every ten years.
[src:sign-language/1964-new-york-world-s-fair-p01] These rules were not immutable; for example, the BIE had recognized the 1939 fair, even though the previous exposition had run for two seasons.
[src:sign-language/1964-new-york-world-s-fair-p01] Moses refused to negotiate with BIE officials and treated them derisively, belittling the BIE as a "bunch of clowns in Paris".
[src:sign-language/1964-new-york-world-s-fair-p01] Due to Moses' behavior, the BIE instead decided to approve the 1962 Seattle World's Fair, and directed its members to not host official exhibits at the 1964 New York World's Fair.
[src:sign-language/1964-new-york-world-s-fair-p01] The WFC planned to issue $500 million in bonds, a figure that was later decreased to $150 million.
[src:sign-language/1964-new-york-world-s-fair-p01] Moses said the 1964 fair would be a "billion-dollar" event, though this included expenses for related projects such as roads and the nearby Shea Stadium.
[src:sign-language/1964-new-york-world-s-fair-p01] The WFC leased about 646 acres (261 ha) from the city government in May 1960.
[src:sign-language/1964-new-york-world-s-fair-p01] Moses hired the former lieutenant governor Charles Poletti and the military engineer William Everett Potter to organize the exhibits.
[src:sign-language/1964-new-york-world-s-fair-p01] A design committee proposed a massive, doughnut-shaped pavilion; Moses rejected the plan and the design committee was forced out by the end of 1959.
[src:sign-language/1964-new-york-world-s-fair-p01] Moses did not devise a master plan for the fair; he wanted to save the WFC money by having exhibitors erect most of their own pavilions, The city government implemented a building code and health code, which Potter enforced.
[src:sign-language/1964-new-york-world-s-fair-p01] Nearly all of the buildings were to be temporary structures.
[src:sign-language/1964-new-york-world-s-fair-p01] The 1964 fair was to be themed "peace through understanding".
[src:sign-language/1964-new-york-world-s-fair-p01] WFC member Jerome Weinstein suggested the motto, which was inspired by an ideal Kopple had wanted for his daughters.
[src:sign-language/1964-new-york-world-s-fair-p01] According to Moses, the fair was intended "to assist in educating the peoples of the world as to the interdependence of nations and the need for universal lasting peace".
[src:sign-language/1964-new-york-world-s-fair-p01] Exhibits were to be divided into five areas, including a transportation area the Port of New York Authority would operate.
[src:sign-language/1964-new-york-world-s-fair-p01] The original plans called for an amusement park area, which was canceled after the WFC failed to find an operator.
[src:sign-language/1964-new-york-world-s-fair-p01] By August 1960, the first ten exhibitors had applied for space at the fair, and architectural blueprints for the fair's first pavilion had been submitted.
[src:sign-language/1964-new-york-world-s-fair-p01] The WFC began sending delegations abroad to invite foreign governments to the fair.
[src:sign-language/1964-new-york-world-s-fair-p01] In late 1960, the group began issuing $67.5 million in promissory notes to fund construction; the WFC later reduced the amount to $64 million, consisting of $40 million in notes plus $24 million from the city.
[src:sign-language/1964-new-york-world-s-fair-p01] The WFC's finance chairman predicted the fair would earn over $200 million.
[src:sign-language/1964-new-york-world-s-fair-p01] By the end of 1960, seven countries had agreed to sponsor exhibits. and one-third of the industrial pavilion sites had been leased.
[src:sign-language/1964-new-york-world-s-fair-p01] Early in 1961, Moses announced the Unisphere would be built as the fair's symbol, and the WFC also hired the detective agency Pinkerton to provide security and first-aid services.
[src:sign-language/1964-new-york-world-s-fair-p01] A report published that January said the fair itself would cost $768 million, although individual exhibitors would pay much of the cost.
[src:sign-language/1964-new-york-world-s-fair-p01] Exhibitors designed their own pavilions and construction contractors hired members of local labor unions to build the structures.
[src:sign-language/1964-new-york-world-s-fair-p01] Wagner predicted 10,000 people would be employed during construction.
[src:sign-language/1964-new-york-world-s-fair-p01] The WFC hosted "preview days" where selected guests could view the construction.
[src:sign-language/1964-new-york-world-s-fair-p01] The Travelers Companies built information centers across the U.S. to promote the fair, and local chapters of the Elks, Kiwanis, and Rotary clubs promoted the fair nationwide.
[src:sign-language/1964-new-york-world-s-fair-p01] The WFC issued collectible medallions in bronze and silver that were manufactured by Medallic Art Company.
[src:sign-language/1964-new-york-world-s-fair-p01] Commemorative postage stamps were issued to celebrate the fair, both inside and outside the U.S.
[src:sign-language/1964-new-york-world-s-fair-p01] Some New York license plates also bore slogans advertising the fair.
[src:sign-language/1964-new-york-world-s-fair-p01] Several hotels were built nearby to accommodate fair visitors, and public transit and roads linking the venue were also upgraded.
[src:sign-language/1964-new-york-world-s-fair-p01] The WFC opened an information office to answer visitors' questions.
[src:sign-language/1964-new-york-world-s-fair-p01] Private businesses promoted their products for the fair, and discounted tickets were sold in advance of the opening.
[src:sign-language/1964-new-york-world-s-fair-p01] William Whipple Jr., the fair's chief engineer, said in September 1960 exhibitors would be able to begin erecting pavilions by 1962.
[src:sign-language/1964-new-york-world-s-fair-p01] Construction of the first building, an administration structure, began in August 1960 and was finished in January 1961.
[src:sign-language/1964-new-york-world-s-fair-p01] In early 1961, almost all of Flushing Meadows–Corona Park was closed to allow the fair's construction, and the Long Island Rail Road's (LIRR) World's Fair station opened.
[src:sign-language/1964-new-york-world-s-fair-p01] Workers moved trees and diverted parts of the Flushing River into tunnels.
[src:sign-language/1964-new-york-world-s-fair-p01] By April 1961, thirty-four countries had accepted invitations to the fair, and the city agreed to spend $24 million improving the park.
[src:sign-language/1964-new-york-world-s-fair-p01] Moses secretly obtained additional funds from the city government; according to Moses's biographer Robert Caro, the city government may have spent as much as $60 million on the fair.
[src:sign-language/1964-new-york-world-s-fair-p01] In May, the WFC announced it would proceed with the planned amusement area around Meadow Lake, hiring the billionaire H.
[src:sign-language/1964-new-york-world-s-fair-p01] By mid-1961, the WFC had privately raised $25 million and was predicting a $53 million profit.
[src:sign-language/1964-new-york-world-s-fair-p01] The groundbreaking ceremony for the first pavilion took place that June.
[src:sign-language/1964-new-york-world-s-fair-p01] The WFC had difficulty selling the remaining bonds; it had sold around $30 million in promissory notes—three quarters of the total—by the end of 1961.
[src:sign-language/1964-new-york-world-s-fair-p01] During the fair's construction, civil-rights activists expressed concerns the WFC's leadership included very few African Americans.
[src:sign-language/1964-new-york-world-s-fair-p01] Moses met with activists but he still did not appoint African Americans to leadership positions, which attracted controversy amid the ongoing civil rights movement.
[src:sign-language/1964-new-york-world-s-fair-p01] The WFC hired an African American executive to the fair's international division in 1962.
[src:sign-language/1964-new-york-world-s-fair-p01] Later that year, New York governor Nelson Rockefeller formed a committee to investigate persistent complaints about discrimination within the WFC.
[src:sign-language/1964-new-york-world-s-fair-p01] By the beginning of 1962, more than 60 nations, the governments of 30 U.S. states, and 50 companies had agreed to exhibit at the fair.
[src:sign-language/1964-new-york-world-s-fair-p01] The WFC also created a scale model of the fairground.
[src:sign-language/1964-new-york-world-s-fair-p01] The LIRR constructed a siding from the Port Washington Branch, allowing trains to deliver material onsite.
[src:sign-language/1964-new-york-world-s-fair-p01] At a luncheon in March that year, Moses said construction had fallen behind schedule.
[src:sign-language/1964-new-york-world-s-fair-p01] The WFC had allocated $6 million to advertise the fair by mid-1962, and Deegan predicted its participants would spend another $75 million of their own money on promotion.
[src:sign-language/1964-new-york-world-s-fair-p01] The WFC tried to attract Latin American countries to the fair.
[src:sign-language/1964-new-york-world-s-fair-p01] By late 1962, exhibits were being finalized and many pavilions were being constructed.
[src:sign-language/1964-new-york-world-s-fair-p01] Either 68 or 71 nations had announced plans for exhibits at the fair by then, though only 35 countries had formally leased space.
[src:sign-language/1964-new-york-world-s-fair-p01] Additionally, 125 businesses had expressed interest, and the WFC had finished installing utilities on the fairground.
[src:sign-language/1964-new-york-world-s-fair-p01] At the end of 1962, a small number of state and international pavilions were being built, while work in the industrial and transportation areas was progressing.
[src:sign-language/1964-new-york-world-s-fair-p01] Groundbreaking ceremonies were hosted for many of the international pavilions.
[src:sign-language/1964-new-york-world-s-fair-p01] In early 1963, the World's Fair Housing Bureau was formed to coordinate the development of hotel rooms for the fair.
[src:sign-language/1964-new-york-world-s-fair-p01] Despite commitments from state and national governments, only some of these governments were actively constructing pavilions.
[src:sign-language/1964-new-york-world-s-fair-p01] The WFC wanted to hire 40 concessionaires and sell 70 intellectual property (IP) licenses, which the corporation hoped would raise $130 million.
[src:sign-language/1964-new-york-world-s-fair-p01] On April 22, 1963, exactly a year before the fair's opening, the U.S.
[src:sign-language/1964-new-york-world-s-fair-p01] Kennedy activated a clock that would count down to the opening.
[src:sign-language/1964-new-york-world-s-fair-p01] Only 48 of the 200 proposed buildings had begun construction, even though construction of all major structures had to be underway by the following month.
[src:sign-language/1964-new-york-world-s-fair-p01] The press building opened that May, and the following month, an insurance syndicate was formed to protect the exhibits.
[src:sign-language/1964-new-york-world-s-fair-p01] By mid-1963, civil-rights groups were protesting the lack of racial diversity in the fair's development, and filed a lawsuit to halt construction.
[src:sign-language/1964-new-york-world-s-fair-p01] That July, Moses denied rumors that construction had fallen behind schedule.
[src:sign-language/1964-new-york-world-s-fair-p01] Materials from overseas began arriving in August 1963, though work on 50 structures had not started by the next month.
[src:sign-language/1964-new-york-world-s-fair-p01] Moses became increasingly hostile toward journalists who doubted that the fair would be completed on time.
[src:sign-language/1964-new-york-world-s-fair-p01] There were also disagreements over discounted tickets for students; Moses opposed the plan but the city government ultimately forced him to sell discounted tickets.
[src:sign-language/1964-new-york-world-s-fair-p01] The first pavilion, the Port Authority Heliport, was opened in October 1963.
[src:sign-language/1964-new-york-world-s-fair-p01] The same month, Hunt resigned as the amusement area's operator following disagreements over ticket prices and rides.
[src:sign-language/1964-new-york-world-s-fair-p01] Work on many of the pavilions was behind schedule due to funding issues, labor shortages, and poor weather.
[src:sign-language/1964-new-york-world-s-fair-p01] There were also labor strikes, exhibitor withdrawals, and continuing racial tensions.
[src:sign-language/1964-new-york-world-s-fair-p01] Despite these difficulties, many pavilions were nearly completed by late 1963, and the WFC had sold 3.8 million advance tickets by the year's end.
[src:sign-language/1964-new-york-world-s-fair-p01] To draw attention to the fair, the WFC displayed models of exhibits at the Time-Life Building in Manhattan.
[src:sign-language/1964-new-york-world-s-fair-p01] Exhibits were installed through late 1963 and early 1964, and the WFC borrowed $3 million to fund the fair's completion.
[src:sign-language/1964-new-york-world-s-fair-p01] In January 1964, the *Chicago Tribune* reported the site was filled with raw material, incomplete building frames, and unpaved roads.
[src:sign-language/1964-new-york-world-s-fair-p01] That month, WFC officials said work on 26 buildings was behind schedule, and they sought to demolish the World of Food pavilion, which would not be ready for the fair's opening.
[src:sign-language/1964-new-york-world-s-fair-p01] The WFC signed a document outlining ways profits from the fair were to be used.
[src:sign-language/1964-new-york-world-s-fair-p01] By that February, most of the major pavilions and attractions were complete, but Whipple estimated up to 10 pavilions would not be finished before the fair's opening.
[src:sign-language/1964-new-york-world-s-fair-p01] The same month, the WFC stopped selling advance tickets, having sold 28 million.
[src:sign-language/1964-new-york-world-s-fair-p01] There were still 4,800 construction workers on site in late March, when the state government began hiring people for the fair.
[src:sign-language/1964-new-york-world-s-fair-p01] Before the fair opened, the WFC had spent $30 million.
[src:sign-language/1964-new-york-world-s-fair-p01] The WFC originally predicted a daily attendance of 225,000.
[src:sign-language/1964-new-york-world-s-fair-p01] Deegan predicted at least 6.7 million foreign visitors, out of an estimated total of 70 million.
[src:sign-language/1964-new-york-world-s-fair-p01] Visitors 13 and older were originally charged the adult admission price of $2.00 (equivalent to $20.76 in 2025), while children 2–12 years old were charged $1.00 (equivalent to $10.38 in 2025).
[src:sign-language/1964-new-york-world-s-fair-p01] The WFC sold discounted tickets in packs of 20; some major companies like AT&T bought hundreds of thousands of tickets for their employees.
[src:sign-language/1964-new-york-world-s-fair-p01] Students paid 25 cents if they visited with their teachers, and the WFC sold certificates that allowed a class of 25 students to enter the fair for $6.25.
[src:sign-language/1964-new-york-world-s-fair-p01] Moses predicted ticket sales of $120 million and a net profit of $40 million.
[src:sign-language/1964-new-york-world-s-fair-p01] Initially, city officials predicted people would spend $5 billion in the city due to the fair, an estimate that was later reduced to $2.5 billion.
[src:sign-language/1964-new-york-world-s-fair-p01] Though the fair employed up to 20,000 people but the WFC directly employed only between 180 and 200 people.
[src:sign-language/1964-new-york-world-s-fair-p01] There were 3,000 Pinkerton employees on the grounds, including firefighters, police officers, medics, matrons, and ticket sellers.
[src:sign-language/1964-new-york-world-s-fair-p01] Nine garbage trucks, nine emergency medical services (EMS) vehicles, 25 police cars, and three fire engines traveled the fairgrounds.
[src:sign-language/1964-new-york-world-s-fair-p01] Nine city health inspectors examined all of the on-site restaurants.
[src:sign-language/1964-new-york-world-s-fair-p01] United Press International (UPI) was the fair's official photographer, while United World Films had exclusive rights to produce and publish films about the fair.
[src:sign-language/1964-new-york-world-s-fair-p01] Allied Maintenance was the only maintenance firm allowed to work at the fair; it charged exorbitant fees, earning $10 million during 1964 alone.
[src:sign-language/1964-new-york-world-s-fair-p01] Allied also handled deliveries during the 1964 season but was replaced the following year with Rentar Corporation.
[src:sign-language/1964-new-york-world-s-fair-p01] Other companies, such as Hertz and Cities Service, sponsored free services or events.
[src:sign-language/1964-new-york-world-s-fair-p01] The WFC selected symbols of a boy and a girl as the fair's mascots.
[src:sign-language/1964-new-york-world-s-fair-p01] Exhibitors were required to operate from 10 am to 10 pm daily, although the fairground opened at 9 am.
[src:sign-language/1964-new-york-world-s-fair-p01] Exhibits were prepared and cleaned throughout the night; the Vatican pavilion was the only attraction with a live-in caretaker.
[src:sign-language/1964-new-york-world-s-fair-p01] Many exhibitors hired racially diverse staff.
[src:sign-language/1964-new-york-world-s-fair-p01] In addition, the WFC required each exhibitor to purchase insurance from Campo & Roberts, which earned $3 million from insurance commissions.
[src:sign-language/1964-new-york-world-s-fair-p01] The WFC did not host official press previews in the weeks before the official opening, though several exhibitors hosted previews of their pavilions.
[src:sign-language/1964-new-york-world-s-fair-p01] The night before the fair opened, the television series *The Bell Telephone Hour* broadcast an opening celebration.
[src:sign-language/1964-new-york-world-s-fair-p01] When the World's Fair officially opened at 9:00 am on April 22, 1964, the first visitor was a college student from New Jersey.
[src:sign-language/1964-new-york-world-s-fair-p01] The opening was celebrated with speeches by Robert Moses, Nelson Rockefeller, and the U.S. president Lyndon B.
[src:sign-language/1964-new-york-world-s-fair-p01] The same day, Johnson dedicated the United States Pavilion, while Rockefeller and Moses dedicated the New York State Pavilion.
[src:sign-language/1964-new-york-world-s-fair-p01] During the opening ceremonies, hundreds of civil-rights activists organized a sit-in and were arrested.
[src:sign-language/1964-new-york-world-s-fair-p01] The civil-rights group Congress of Racial Equality (CORE) proposed a "stall-in" to block roads leading to the fair, but few activists participated.
[src:sign-language/1964-new-york-world-s-fair-p01] The opening ceremony attracted 90,000 attendees, fewer than half of the predicted number, in part due to inclement weather.
[src:sign-language/1964-new-york-world-s-fair-p01] The WFC banned picketing on the grounds, prompting lawsuits from civil-rights groups; a federal judge later ruled protesters could give out handbills to passers-by.
[src:sign-language/1964-new-york-world-s-fair-p01] The fair needed 220,000 daily visitors to recover its operating expenses of $300,000 per day.
[src:sign-language/1964-new-york-world-s-fair-p01] In its first week, the fair recorded nearly a million visitors, and 150,000 daily visitors—60 percent of initial projections—in the first month.
[src:sign-language/1964-new-york-world-s-fair-p01] Several problems arose; disputes occurred over labor unions, maintenance fees, and a mural in the Jordan pavilion.
[src:sign-language/1964-new-york-world-s-fair-p01] Thefts and breakdowns regularly occurred.
[src:sign-language/1964-new-york-world-s-fair-p01] Exhibitors complained about high rental rates and insufficient maintenance of the fairground.
[src:sign-language/1964-new-york-world-s-fair-p01] The Lake Amusement Area was especially unprofitable; it had few attractions and was difficult to access.
[src:sign-language/1964-new-york-world-s-fair-p01] The Texas pavilion's show in the Amusement Area, "To Broadway with Love", closed in July 1964, and the "Wonderwork" show nearby also closed before the first season ended.
[src:sign-language/1964-new-york-world-s-fair-p01] Many of the most-popular exhibits charged an additional fee, and visitors often did not bring enough money for food or for high-priced exhibits.
[src:sign-language/1964-new-york-world-s-fair-p01] The WFC unsuccessfully attempted to entice visitors by offering discounts to taxi drivers and improving fairground lighting, and the WFC was planning promotional campaigns by the end of June.
[src:sign-language/1964-new-york-world-s-fair-p01] Walter Thompson Company advertised the fair in New York City–area media.
[src:sign-language/1964-new-york-world-s-fair-p01] By mid-1964, some exhibitors had gone out of business, including the two largest shows in the Lake Amusement Area.
[src:sign-language/1964-new-york-world-s-fair-p01] Employees, especially the 4,000 college students who worked the fair, faced occupational burnout.
[src:sign-language/1964-new-york-world-s-fair-p01] Despite the troubles, the WFC was able to buy back one quarter of its promissory notes in mid-1964, and to attract visitors, exhibitors publicly downplayed their grievances with the WFC.
[src:sign-language/1964-new-york-world-s-fair-p01] The industrial and international pavilions were more profitable than the amusement area, whose financial troubles did not bother Moses.
[src:sign-language/1964-new-york-world-s-fair-p01] The fair had difficulty attracting more than 200,000 daily visitors, even during July and August when students were on summer break.
[src:sign-language/1964-new-york-world-s-fair-p01] The fair recorded 13.4 million visitors by the season's midpoint in July 1964, and it received 5.8 million visitors that August, the highest of any month during the 1964 season.
[src:sign-language/1964-new-york-world-s-fair-p01] Nearly half of visitors came from the New York City area, and prospective visitors expressed fears about crime and unrest.
[src:sign-language/1964-new-york-world-s-fair-p01] Attendance declined significantly in September when children returned to school.
[src:sign-language/1964-new-york-world-s-fair-p01] In response, Moses said journalists were tarnishing the fair's reputation and accused them of suppressing attendance.
[src:sign-language/1964-new-york-world-s-fair-p01] An exhibitors' committee made several recommendations for increasing attendance but Moses rejected nearly all of them.
[src:sign-language/1964-new-york-world-s-fair-p01] The fair closed for the season on October 18, 1964.
[src:sign-language/1964-new-york-world-s-fair-p01] There had been 33 million visitors, including 27 million who paid admission.
[src:sign-language/1964-new-york-world-s-fair-p01] *The New York Times* cited several reasons for the reduced attendance figures; these included fears of crime, lengthy queues, and high prices.
[src:sign-language/1964-new-york-world-s-fair-p01] The WFC had significantly overpaid several contractors, and the fair's operating expenditures during 1964 amounted to $33.3 million, twice the original budget.
[src:sign-language/1964-new-york-world-s-fair-p01] Moses had projected a $53 million surplus, but the surplus stood at only $12.6 million at season's end, barely enough to pay back the city government.
[src:sign-language/1964-new-york-world-s-fair-p01] The WFC reduced its estimated total profit for both seasons to $30 million.
[src:sign-language/1964-new-york-world-s-fair-p01] Despite the financial problems, many industrial pavilions had long queues and tens of thousands of daily visitors, and the General Motors and Vatican pavilions each saw more than 10 million visitors during 1964.
[src:sign-language/1964-new-york-world-s-fair-p01] *The New York Times* reported many international exhibitors were pleased with the fair but wanted someone else to operate it.
[src:sign-language/1964-new-york-world-s-fair-p01] Between the 1964 and 1965 seasons, the WFC hired 400 security guards to oversee the fairground, though exhibitors were obligated to maintain and guard their own pavilions.
[src:sign-language/1964-new-york-world-s-fair-p01] The WFC planned to spend $1.3 million on renovations, and 3,000 workers began winterizing the fairground in November 1964.
[src:sign-language/1964-new-york-world-s-fair-p01] The WFC planned to create a promotional film and advertisements for the fair, and it kept some of the paths and fountains illuminated.
[src:sign-language/1964-new-york-world-s-fair-p01] Deegan said several pavilions would be renovated and 12 new restaurants would be added.
[src:sign-language/1964-new-york-world-s-fair-p01] Moses also traveled around the world to persuade foreign exhibitors to display additional artifacts, such as a Gutenberg Bible and Spanish artwork, during 1965.
[src:sign-language/1964-new-york-world-s-fair-p01] WFC officials said attendance would rise during the 1965 season, and anticipated 37.5 million visitors.
[src:sign-language/1964-new-york-world-s-fair-p01] The prediction was unrealistic; previous world's fairs typically had fewer visitors during their second season and no new pavilions were being planned.
[src:sign-language/1964-new-york-world-s-fair-p01] In its balance sheet, the WFC counted profits from advance ticket sales as part of its income for 1964, which meant revenue would be much lower than expected during 1965.
[src:sign-language/1964-new-york-world-s-fair-p01] Unless the fair had at least 37.5 million visitors in 1965, it would not be profitable.
[src:sign-language/1964-new-york-world-s-fair-p01] WFC officials, fearing reprisal from Moses, waited weeks to tell him about the fair's financial troubles.
[src:sign-language/1964-new-york-world-s-fair-p01] In November 1964, Moses told Wagner the WFC might not be able to repay the city's $24 million loan.
[src:sign-language/1964-new-york-world-s-fair-p01] The WFC's financial advisors raised suspicions of financial mismanagement the next month.
[src:sign-language/1964-new-york-world-s-fair-p01] In January 1965, several of the WFC's financial advisors quit following bitter disputes, and the WFC requested $3.5 million to reopen the fair.
[src:sign-language/1964-new-york-world-s-fair-p01] The city controller Abraham Beame began auditing the WFC, and the WFC fired Deegan's public-relations firm, which had been receiving $300,000 annually for four years, following criticism over the firm's compensation.
[src:sign-language/1964-new-york-world-s-fair-p01] The WFC's internal audit found a $17.5 million deficit, but lawsuits delayed Beame's audit for several months.
[src:sign-language/1964-new-york-world-s-fair-p01] By February 1965, at least 14 exhibitors in the 1964 season had declared bankruptcy.
[src:sign-language/1964-new-york-world-s-fair-p01] Franklin National Bank offered to lend the WFC $3.5 million, but the WFC indicated it needed only $1 million.
[src:sign-language/1964-new-york-world-s-fair-p01] Though city officials wanted to remove Moses as the WFC's president, he retained his position.
[src:sign-language/1964-new-york-world-s-fair-p01] When Moses said he would spend $6.4 million to renovate Flushing Meadows–Corona Park before repaying debts, the WFC's finance chairman resigned.
[src:sign-language/1964-new-york-world-s-fair-p01] Two Marine Midland Bank branches provided a $1 million loan to the WFC that March, which the WFC repaid two months later.
[src:sign-language/1964-new-york-world-s-fair-p01] During the off-season, several exhibitors renovated and modified their pavilions, spending over $7 million between them.
[src:sign-language/1964-new-york-world-s-fair-p01] At least 50 exhibits were upgraded and five major attractions were added, along with free entertainments and science demonstrations.
[src:sign-language/1964-new-york-world-s-fair-p01] New artworks and films were added to several pavilions.
[src:sign-language/1964-new-york-world-s-fair-p01] The struggling Lake Amusement Area became the Lake Area.
[src:sign-language/1964-new-york-world-s-fair-p01] The WFC asked the New York City Transit Authority to increase subway service to the fair, and 26 exhibitors collaborated on a promotional campaign.
[src:sign-language/1964-new-york-world-s-fair-p01] Fifty-three exhibitors proposed naming the first week of the 1965 season Fair Festival Week, to which Wagner agreed.
[src:sign-language/1964-new-york-world-s-fair-p01] The WFC produced a promotional film titled *To the Fair*, and individual exhibitors produced their own films.
[src:sign-language/1964-new-york-world-s-fair-p01] To reduce its debts, the WFC decreased its budget for the 1965 season and dismissed some employees.
[src:sign-language/1964-new-york-world-s-fair-p01] More than 150,000 people attended the reopening of the fair on April 21, 1965.
[src:sign-language/1964-new-york-world-s-fair-p01] The Ethiopian long-distance runners Abebe Bikila and Mamo Wolde participated in a ceremonial half marathon, running from Central Park in Manhattan to Singer Bowl at the fairground.
[src:sign-language/1964-new-york-world-s-fair-p01] Unlike the 1964 opening ceremony, no protests occurred at the fair's reopening, and almost all exhibits were completed on time.
[src:sign-language/1964-new-york-world-s-fair-p01] For the 1965 season, adult admission fees were raised to $2.50 (equivalent to $25.54 in 2025).
[src:sign-language/1964-new-york-world-s-fair-p01] During the first 20 days of the 1965 season, attendance declined 22 percent compared with the same time period in 1964, putting many exhibitors at risk of bankruptcy.
[src:sign-language/1964-new-york-world-s-fair-p01] In addition, fewer visitors were paying at the gates because more than half of them carried advance tickets.
[src:sign-language/1964-new-york-world-s-fair-p01] Exhibitors requested a reduction in admission fees, and that a reduced-price evening admission ticket be sold.
[src:sign-language/1964-new-york-world-s-fair-p01] Moses refused both proposals, and several exhibitors threatened to close their pavilions before retracting.
[src:sign-language/1964-new-york-world-s-fair-p01] At the beginning of the 1965 season, there were issues such as race-related protests, Vietnam War protests, a controversy over a racially insensitive song in one pavilion, and disputes between Jewish and Arab exhibitors.
[src:sign-language/1964-new-york-world-s-fair-p01] Vandalism also increased due to the reduced police presence, and a fairgoer was murdered that May.
[src:sign-language/1964-new-york-world-s-fair-p01] WFC officials also tried to invalidate their January 1964 agreement for disbursing the fair's profits, and exhibitors continued to lose money due to lower-than-expected attendance.
[src:sign-language/1964-new-york-world-s-fair-p01] Fewer visitors came during the evening, but the WFC again rejected a proposal for discounted evening admission in July 1965.
[src:sign-language/1964-new-york-world-s-fair-p01] Despite increased attendance in mid-1965, the fair continued to record decreased revenue compared with 1964.
[src:sign-language/1964-new-york-world-s-fair-p01] Many exhibitors recorded substantial losses from the costs of their pavilions.
[src:sign-language/1964-new-york-world-s-fair-p01] By August 1965, the WFC was preparing to clear the fairground after the fair, though 13 exhibitors had declared bankruptcy and could not afford to demolish or move their pavilions.
[src:sign-language/1964-new-york-world-s-fair-p01] Beame's interim report, which was published at the end of August, found the WFC had squandered money by not awarding contracts through competitive bidding and by spending nearly everything it had on expenses it incurred before and during 1964.
[src:sign-language/1964-new-york-world-s-fair-p01] Despite Moses's denials of wrongdoing, Queens district attorney Frank D.
[src:sign-language/1964-new-york-world-s-fair-p01] O'Connor opened a criminal inquiry into the WFC shortly afterward.
[src:sign-language/1964-new-york-world-s-fair-p01] Moses installed highway signs promoting the fair and refused to remove them, even after city traffic commissioner Henry A.
[src:sign-language/1964-new-york-world-s-fair-p01] Barnes called the signs a safety hazard.
[src:sign-language/1964-new-york-world-s-fair-p01] By mid-September, estimates of the fair's total attendance had been reduced from 70 to 50 million.
[src:sign-language/1964-new-york-world-s-fair-p01] By the end of September, the fair had recorded 17 million visitors during the 1965 season, less than half the number of visitors needed to break even.
[src:sign-language/1964-new-york-world-s-fair-p01] At this point, the WFC had barely enough money to pay its weekly expenses.
[src:sign-language/1964-new-york-world-s-fair-p01] Toward the end of the 1965 season, there was a sustained increase in attendance, and the fair recorded more than 250,000 daily visitors for three consecutive weeks.
[src:sign-language/1964-new-york-world-s-fair-p01] Exhibitors worried potential visitors would be dissuaded by the overcrowding.
[src:sign-language/1964-new-york-world-s-fair-p01] Stern attributed the increase in attendance to a prevailing feeling the 1964 fair would be one of the last lavish world's fairs.
[src:sign-language/1964-new-york-world-s-fair-p01] Pope Paul VI visited the fair on October 4, 1965, during the first-ever papal visit to the United States.
[src:sign-language/1964-new-york-world-s-fair-p01] The fair closed on October 17, 1965, and recorded its highest-ever daily attendance of 446,953 on its final day.
[src:sign-language/1964-new-york-world-s-fair-p01] The fair's final day was chaotic, with reports of vandalism and theft.
[src:sign-language/1964-new-york-world-s-fair-p01] In total, the fair had recorded 51,607,448 admissions, seven million more than the 1939 fair and ten million more than Expo 58.
[src:sign-language/1964-new-york-world-s-fair-p01] The GM and Vatican pavilions had been the most popular.
[src:sign-language/1964-new-york-world-s-fair-p01] The fair had lost an additional $1 million in 1965 and had a deficit of up to $40 million at its closing; *The New York Times* partly attributed the fair's underperformance to Moses's stubborn attitude and refusal to take advice.
[src:sign-language/1964-new-york-world-s-fair-p01] The fairground was divided into five regions.
[src:sign-language/1964-new-york-world-s-fair-p01] Exhibits for individual U.S. states and the U.S. federal government were concentrated in the Federal & State Area at the center of the fairground near the Unisphere.
[src:sign-language/1964-new-york-world-s-fair-p01] The international exhibits were concentrated in the International Area—a group of pavilions surrounding the Unisphere.
[src:sign-language/1964-new-york-world-s-fair-p01] Industry pavilions were concentrated around the Industrial Area on the eastern end near the Van Wyck Expressway.
[src:sign-language/1964-new-york-world-s-fair-p01] The Transportation Area was on the western side of the fairground.
[src:sign-language/1964-new-york-world-s-fair-p01] South of the Long Island Expressway, connected with the rest of the fair only via one overpass, was the Lake Amusement Area (known as the Lake Area during 1965).
[src:sign-language/1964-new-york-world-s-fair-p01] Eight gates provided access to the fairground.
[src:sign-language/1964-new-york-world-s-fair-p01] The 1964 World's Fair had 139 pavilions on opening day, in addition to 34 concessions and shows.
[src:sign-language/1964-new-york-world-s-fair-p01] Of the pavilions and shows, either 121 or 124 were free, and the rest required an additional payment.
[src:sign-language/1964-new-york-world-s-fair-p01] Scattered across the fairground were 5,300 trees, 3,500 benches, 1,400 telephones, and 60 mailboxes.
[src:sign-language/1964-new-york-world-s-fair-p01] There were also bank branches, picnic areas, and restrooms.
[src:sign-language/1964-new-york-world-s-fair-p01] Accessible bathrooms, wheelchair rental stands, and Braille guidebooks were provided for disabled visitors.
[src:sign-language/1964-new-york-world-s-fair-p01] There were also several hotels nearby, albeit few campgrounds.
[src:sign-language/1964-new-york-world-s-fair-p01] A spokesman for the 1964 fair said the exposition was supposed to be "cultural and sophisticated", and Deegan claimed that the exposition would be the "greatest single event in history".
[src:sign-language/1964-new-york-world-s-fair-p01] Each section of the fair was designed in several architectural styles, and many of the pavilions were designed in a Space Age style.
[src:sign-language/1964-new-york-world-s-fair-p01] Some pavilions used experimental designs; for example, the Bell System Pavilion was supported by massive cantilevers, while the IBM Pavilion was shaped like a giant egg.
[src:sign-language/1964-new-york-world-s-fair-p01] Most of the structures were designed so they could easily be demolished after the fair and rebuilt elsewhere.
[src:sign-language/1964-new-york-world-s-fair-p01] Any person or entity who could afford to rent the land and construct a pavilion could rent exhibition space at the fair.
[src:sign-language/1964-new-york-world-s-fair-p01] Thus, the space was dominated by large corporations.
[src:sign-language/1964-new-york-world-s-fair-p01] Private companies spent a combined $300 million on their pavilions.
[src:sign-language/1964-new-york-world-s-fair-p01] The Big Three car manufacturers—Chrysler, Ford, and General Motors—alone spent a combined $110 million on attractions such as Chrysler's artificial islands, Ford's Magic Skyway, and General Motors' Futurama car ride.
[src:sign-language/1964-new-york-world-s-fair-p01] Twenty-three state pavilions were built.
[src:sign-language/1964-new-york-world-s-fair-p01] The fair included exhibits from 24 U.S. states; these were Alaska, Florida, Hawaii, Illinois, Louisiana, Maryland, Minnesota, Missouri, Montana, New Jersey, New York, Oklahoma, Tennessee, Texas, West Virginia, Wisconsin, and the six states in New England.
[src:sign-language/1964-new-york-world-s-fair-p01] New York City had its own pavilion, as did the neighborhood of Hollywood, Los Angeles, California.
[src:sign-language/1964-new-york-world-s-fair-p01] Nineteen of the state pavilions were in the Federal and State Area, and three of the other four state pavilions were clustered around Meadow Lake at the southern end of the fair.
[src:sign-language/1964-new-york-world-s-fair-p01] None of the state governments had to pay rent for the land, but they had to fund the buildings.
[src:sign-language/1964-new-york-world-s-fair-p01] Twenty states and Washington, D.C., did not pay for exhibits at the fair.
[src:sign-language/1964-new-york-world-s-fair-p01] There were 45 pavilions in the International Area, most of which featured exhibits from foreign countries.
[src:sign-language/1964-new-york-world-s-fair-p01] Individual exhibits were presented by 66 nations, including the United States, whose pavilion was in the Federal and State Area.
[src:sign-language/1964-new-york-world-s-fair-p01] If nations that were represented only by one city or region are included, the fair had attractions from 80 countries.
[src:sign-language/1964-new-york-world-s-fair-p01] Foreign nations rented land from the WFC, and paid for staff lodgings, food, and other expenses.
[src:sign-language/1964-new-york-world-s-fair-p01] Many nations from Asia, Africa, and Central and South America, though relatively few from Europe, exhibited at the fair.
[src:sign-language/1964-new-york-world-s-fair-p01] Some countries, such as the United Kingdom, France, and Italy, boycotted the fair because the BIE had not approved it.
[src:sign-language/1964-new-york-world-s-fair-p01] Because of a lack of participation from BIE members, only six major countries—Egypt, India, Indonesia, Japan, Mexico, and Pakistan—had official exhibits at the fair.
[src:sign-language/1964-new-york-world-s-fair-p01] Some BIE member countries hosted unofficial exhibits or were represented by those of private companies, and several countries were represented solely by an industry exhibit.
[src:sign-language/1964-new-york-world-s-fair-p01] Other countries were represented by regional pavilions, such as those for the Caribbean and Africa.
[src:sign-language/1964-new-york-world-s-fair-p01] Many of the international pavilions sold merchandise.
[src:sign-language/1964-new-york-world-s-fair-p01] The Industrial Area had 43 pavilions, representing nearly 350 American companies.
[src:sign-language/1964-new-york-world-s-fair-p01] Most of the companies were consolidated within four exhibit buildings, though about 36 companies had their own pavilions.
[src:sign-language/1964-new-york-world-s-fair-p01] Corporations rented land from the WFC, while religious organizations were not required to pay for their space.
[src:sign-language/1964-new-york-world-s-fair-p01] Large firms such as Bell Telephone Company, DuPont, IBM, Kodak, RCA, The Travelers Companies, and US Royal Tires participated.
[src:sign-language/1964-new-york-world-s-fair-p01] The 1964 fair included only a few companies in the food, chemical, tobacco, cosmetic, or pharmaceutical industries and did not include any non-American car manufacturers.
[src:sign-language/1964-new-york-world-s-fair-p01] Transportation companies, including the Big Three car makers, displayed products in the Transportation Area of the fairground.
[src:sign-language/1964-new-york-world-s-fair-p01] Several of the industry pavilions offered free merchandise or other sponsorships, which often attracted customers.
[src:sign-language/1964-new-york-world-s-fair-p01] Moses provided about 7 acres (2.8 ha) of land for religious groups and invited every major sect of Christianity to the fair.
[src:sign-language/1964-new-york-world-s-fair-p01] Eight religious pavilions were built, each of which was staffed by volunteers.
[src:sign-language/1964-new-york-world-s-fair-p01] Some exhibits were planned but never built, such as the Soviet and Israel pavilions, but were displayed on official maps, causing confusion among visitors.
[src:sign-language/1964-new-york-world-s-fair-p01] In addition to pavilions, the Lake Area included several rides and attractions during 1964.
[src:sign-language/1964-new-york-world-s-fair-p01] John Ringling North operated a circus that performed in a 5,000-seat tent.
[src:sign-language/1964-new-york-world-s-fair-p01] The amusement area also included a children's play area, a puppet show, a porpoise show, and other amusements.
[src:sign-language/1964-new-york-world-s-fair-p01] A lake cruise traveled off the shore of Meadow Lake and an early log flume ride was also installed at the fair.
[src:sign-language/1964-new-york-world-s-fair-p01] A replica of the ship *Santa María* was displayed in the lake.
[src:sign-language/1964-new-york-world-s-fair-p01] There was a 10,000-seat outdoor theater in the amusement area as well.
[src:sign-language/1964-new-york-world-s-fair-p01] Two Coney Island carousels were combined to form the Flushing Meadows Carousel.
[src:sign-language/1964-new-york-world-s-fair-p01] The Florida pavilion took over much of the Lake Area in 1965, and two amusement areas called Carnival and Continental Park were added.
[src:sign-language/1964-new-york-world-s-fair-p01] Outside the Lake Area were the Fiesta Playground and the Sculpture Continuum Playground.
[src:sign-language/1964-new-york-world-s-fair-p01] The American Machine and Foundry Company constructed a suspended monorail with two 4,000-foot-long (1,200 m) tracks in the Lake Area.
[src:sign-language/1964-new-york-world-s-fair-p01] The line had seven 80-passenger, two-car-long trains.
[src:sign-language/1964-new-york-world-s-fair-p01] Another transport attraction at the fair was the Swiss Sky Ride, a ski lift or aerial gondola that was sponsored by the Government of Switzerland.
[src:sign-language/1964-new-york-world-s-fair-p01] During the 1964 season, visitors could rent one of 147 Greyhound Escorters, which were driven by chauffeurs.
[src:sign-language/1964-new-york-world-s-fair-p01] Sixty-one Glide-a-Ride trolleys also served the fairground during both seasons.
[src:sign-language/1964-new-york-world-s-fair-p01] The fairground was accessed via highways on Long Island that had been upgraded.
[src:sign-language/1964-new-york-world-s-fair-p01] An expanded World's Fair Marina provided access via Flushing Bay.
[src:sign-language/1964-new-york-world-s-fair-p01] The fair was also served by a short-lived ferry service to Manhattan, as well as other ferry routes to ports in New York and New Jersey.
[src:sign-language/1964-new-york-world-s-fair-p01] A helicopter shuttle provided services to the Pan Am Building and Lower Manhattan heliports.
[src:sign-language/1964-new-york-world-s-fair-p01] Local buses, airport shuttle buses, the New York City Subway, and the Long Island Rail Road (LIRR) also stopped near the fairground.
[src:sign-language/1964-new-york-world-s-fair-p01] The subway cars R33S and R36WF were constructed for the number seven route that served Willets Point station near the fair.
[src:sign-language/1964-new-york-world-s-fair-p01] Although a dedicated subway line had served the 1939 fair, no such route was built for 1964.
[src:sign-language/1964-new-york-world-s-fair-p01] A luxury bus service carried "distinguished guests" to and from the fair.
[src:sign-language/1964-new-york-world-s-fair-p01] There were 20,000 parking spaces, and shuttle buses transported people from the parking lots to the main gate.
[src:sign-language/1964-new-york-world-s-fair-p01] The fairground had nine fountains; the fountains of progress north and south, the fountains of the fairs east and west, the lunar fountain, the solar fountain, the astral fountain, the fountain of the continents, and the fountain of the planets and two reflecting pools.
[src:sign-language/1964-new-york-world-s-fair-p01] Seven of the fountains had custom designs, although none have survived.
[src:sign-language/1964-new-york-world-s-fair-p01] At the center of the fair was the Unisphere, which was constructed by American Bridge Company.
[src:sign-language/1964-new-york-world-s-fair-p01] Weighing 700,000 pounds (317,515 kg), the globe was created to symbolize "man's achievements on a shrinking globe in an expanding universe".
[src:sign-language/1964-new-york-world-s-fair-p01] The Fountain of the Planets (Pool of Industry), which is located at the far eastern end of Flushing Meadows–Corona Park, could spray water up to 625 feet (191 m) high, and it hosted nightly fireworks displays and music performances.
[src:sign-language/1964-new-york-world-s-fair-p01] The Unisphere and Fountain of the Planets are connected via the Fountain of the Fairs, which included a five-section reflecting pool and two rectangular pools.
[src:sign-language/1964-new-york-world-s-fair-p01] The fairground had 28 mi (45 km), 39 mi (63 km), or 40 mi (64 km) of paths, and numerous plazas.
[src:sign-language/1964-new-york-world-s-fair-p01] Throughout the fairground were information booths operated by Greyhound Bus.
[src:sign-language/1964-new-york-world-s-fair-p01] Near the northern end of the fairground was a customs building, where customs officials examined items bound for the fair's international pavilions and concessionaires.
[src:sign-language/1964-new-york-world-s-fair-p01] There was a press building next to the Grand Central Parkway, with a reporters' bullpen, offices for major news agencies, a press conference room, and offices.
[src:sign-language/1964-new-york-world-s-fair-p01] The on-site, 22-room Atomedic Hospital was constantly staffed, and there were five first-aid stations.
[src:sign-language/1964-new-york-world-s-fair-p01] About 300 closed-circuit televisions (CCTVs) were installed across the fairground, and a film studio for independent filmmakers was also built.
[src:sign-language/1964-new-york-world-s-fair-p01] Pinkerton matrons operated a lost-child bureau with activities and games for lost children.
[src:sign-language/1964-new-york-world-s-fair-p02] Foreign cultures and American technologies were featured at the fair.
[src:sign-language/1964-new-york-world-s-fair-p02] While WFC rules technically prevented the fair's officials from influencing the design or contents of any exhibits, the WFC retained a significant influence on the contents of exhibits.
[src:sign-language/1964-new-york-world-s-fair-p02] For example, developing nations were encouraged to show their art and culture rather than technology, and WFC officials pressured Islamic nations to emphasize their religion.
[src:sign-language/1964-new-york-world-s-fair-p02] The fair had a large number of restaurants and eateries.
[src:sign-language/1964-new-york-world-s-fair-p02] When it opened, there were between 110 and 114 eateries, 61 of which were within pavilions.
[src:sign-language/1964-new-york-world-s-fair-p02] There were six specialty restaurants and 25 fine-dining restaurants operated by Brass Rail.
[src:sign-language/1964-new-york-world-s-fair-p02] Restaurant Associates was contracted to operate several of the restaurants but its contract was canceled because of a dispute over signage, and Brass Rail instead received the contract.
[src:sign-language/1964-new-york-world-s-fair-p02] Ten of Brass Rail's restaurants were designed by Victor Lundy and had canopies shaped like bunches of white balloons.
[src:sign-language/1964-new-york-world-s-fair-p02] For the 1965 season, the fair was expanded to include 198 restaurants.
[src:sign-language/1964-new-york-world-s-fair-p02] Cuisine sold at the fair included Belgian waffles, 7 Up drinks, dumplings, pizza, tacos, kimchi, Turkish coffee, tandoori chicken, and hummus.
[src:sign-language/1964-new-york-world-s-fair-p02] Many of these dishes became popular in New York City and in the U.S. after the fair closed.
[src:sign-language/1964-new-york-world-s-fair-p02] The Thailand pavilion included North America's first Thai restaurant, while the Malaysia pavilion served Tiger Beer and satay.
[src:sign-language/1964-new-york-world-s-fair-p02] During the 1964 season, many meals cost 99 cents because any food below $1 could not be taxed.
[src:sign-language/1964-new-york-world-s-fair-p02] Brewers spent millions of dollars persuading exhibitors to sell their beers.
[src:sign-language/1964-new-york-world-s-fair-p02] There were more than 30 entertainment events at the fair.
[src:sign-language/1964-new-york-world-s-fair-p02] Moses disdained carnival-style attractions, saying there would be "no whiskered women, tattooed giants, nudes on ice ...
[src:sign-language/1964-new-york-world-s-fair-p02] The appeal of a world's fair should not be entirely below the Adam's apple".
[src:sign-language/1964-new-york-world-s-fair-p02] As the WFC's president, Moses reserved the right to ban any project from the fair.
[src:sign-language/1964-new-york-world-s-fair-p02] Shows that appealed to prurient interests, like semi-nude dancing, were excluded.
[src:sign-language/1964-new-york-world-s-fair-p02] An exception was the adult-only, musical puppet show *Les Poupées de Paris* (The Dolls of Paris).
[src:sign-language/1964-new-york-world-s-fair-p02] The lack of adult shows may have contributed to the amusement area's unpopularity in 1964.
[src:sign-language/1964-new-york-world-s-fair-p02] The ban on adult shows was relaxed in 1965, and nine discotheques opened at the fair during that season.
[src:sign-language/1964-new-york-world-s-fair-p02] That May, a striptease show in the Louisiana pavilion lasted two performances before it was canceled.
[src:sign-language/1964-new-york-world-s-fair-p02] Musical and theatrical performances took place at several pavilions, and there were fireworks and water shows at the Pool of Industry.
[src:sign-language/1964-new-york-world-s-fair-p02] Among the theatrical shows were the revues *To Broadway With Love*, *Wonder World*—which lasted two months— and *Summer Time Revue*.
[src:sign-language/1964-new-york-world-s-fair-p02] DuPont presented a musical revue in its own pavilion, *The Wonderful World of Chemistry*.
[src:sign-language/1964-new-york-world-s-fair-p02] A controversial minstrel show in the Louisiana pavilion was canceled after two days.
[src:sign-language/1964-new-york-world-s-fair-p02] International pavilions, such as the African, Indonesia, and Spain pavilions, also hosted dance and other live shows.
[src:sign-language/1964-new-york-world-s-fair-p02] Sporting events, such as wrestling, boxing, gymnastics, fencing, judo, and weightlifting, took place at the fair.
[src:sign-language/1964-new-york-world-s-fair-p02] Some of these events were presented as part of the 1964 Summer Olympics tryouts in New York City.
[src:sign-language/1964-new-york-world-s-fair-p02] Other shows included the ice-skating show *Dick Button's Ice-Travaganza* at the New York City Pavilion, and the Auto Thrill Show in the Transportation Area.
[src:sign-language/1964-new-york-world-s-fair-p02] *To Broadway With Love* and the *Ice-Travaganza* closed within a few months of the fair's opening.
[src:sign-language/1964-new-york-world-s-fair-p02] A parade traveled across the fairground every day.
[src:sign-language/1964-new-york-world-s-fair-p02] The evangelist Billy Graham gave daily sermons at the Billy Graham Pavilion.
[src:sign-language/1964-new-york-world-s-fair-p02] The fairground did not emphasize music, although a "World's Fair Festival" took place at Lincoln Center in Manhattan.
[src:sign-language/1964-new-york-world-s-fair-p02] Popular and classical music was broadcast from 800 luminaries around the fairground.
[src:sign-language/1964-new-york-world-s-fair-p02] The fair also had an official band; Cities Service's World's Band of America, a 50-piece ensemble, was headed by the conductor Paul Lavalle.
[src:sign-language/1964-new-york-world-s-fair-p02] Other ensembles, including Guy Lombardo, the United States Marine Band, and the United States Navy Steel Band, performed throughout the fair.
[src:sign-language/1964-new-york-world-s-fair-p02] During 1964, the amusement area hosted rock-and-roll concerts that were popular among local youth; Moses, who abhorred the genre, canceled these concerts when he learned about them.
[src:sign-language/1964-new-york-world-s-fair-p02] The fairground contained about 40 movie theaters, most of which were housed within pavilions, for which fifty films were produced.
[src:sign-language/1964-new-york-world-s-fair-p02] These included several religious films: *Parable* at the Protestant and Orthodox pavilion; *Man in the 5th Dimension* at the Billy Graham pavilion; and *Man's Search for Happiness* at the LDS pavilion.
[src:sign-language/1964-new-york-world-s-fair-p02] The Johnson's Wax pavilion screened a film titled *To Be Alive!*, which later won an Academy Award.
[src:sign-language/1964-new-york-world-s-fair-p02] The WFC produced a film promoting the fair in seven languages in 1964.
[src:sign-language/1964-new-york-world-s-fair-p02] Originally, the WFC made no effort to coordinate art exhibitions at the 1964 World's Fair, and Moses did not wish to subsidize art exhibits on the fairground, nor did he want to pay for an art pavilion himself.
[src:sign-language/1964-new-york-world-s-fair-p02] After commentators spoke about the lack of art at the fair, Moses changed his mind and allowed states to display art in their pavilions.
[src:sign-language/1964-new-york-world-s-fair-p02] Ten pop artists designed art for the New York State Pavilion's Theaterama, and the Fine Arts pavilion displayed 250 contemporary artists' work.
[src:sign-language/1964-new-york-world-s-fair-p02] Foreign nations also displayed art and artifacts at the fair.
[src:sign-language/1964-new-york-world-s-fair-p02] Spain displayed works from artists such as Francisco Goya, El Greco, Joan Miró, Pablo Picasso, and Diego Velázquez.
[src:sign-language/1964-new-york-world-s-fair-p02] The United Arab Republic displayed artifacts from several historical eras; the Sudan pavilion displayed a 1,300-year-old Madonna fresco; the Jordan pavilion showed the Dead Sea Scrolls; and the Republic of China pavilion displayed Chinese jade.
[src:sign-language/1964-new-york-world-s-fair-p02] During the 1965 season, the Mexico pavilion displayed art, including Mesoamerican pieces and works by José Clemente Orozco, Diego Rivera, David Alfaro Siqueiros, and Rufino Tamayo.
[src:sign-language/1964-new-york-world-s-fair-p02] Though art was also displayed in gift shops throughout the fair, WFC officials generally only publicized artwork that was exhibited in pavilions.
[src:sign-language/1964-new-york-world-s-fair-p02] There were 95 sculptures at the fair, including five permanent sculptures, four which remain in Flushing Meadows–Corona Park: *Forms in Transit* by Theodore Roszak, *Freedom of the Human Spirit* by Marshall Fredericks, *Free Form* by José de Rivera, and *Rocket Thrower* by Donald De Lue.
[src:sign-language/1964-new-york-world-s-fair-p02] *Armillary Sphere* by Paul Manship, was vandalized and the remaining pieces were stolen in 1980.
[src:sign-language/1964-new-york-world-s-fair-p02] The temporary sculptures included *Pietà* by Michelangelo at the Vatican pavilion, which was one of the fair's most-popular exhibits.
[src:sign-language/1964-new-york-world-s-fair-p02] The 1964 World's Fair introduced and showed many consumer products, in what one magazine called "the ultimate marketing bonanza of [its] time".
[src:sign-language/1964-new-york-world-s-fair-p02] Color television was popularized at the fair, and the Ford Mustang was launched just before its appearance at the fair.
[src:sign-language/1964-new-york-world-s-fair-p02] The fair also displayed technologies such as Picturephones and IBM computers, as well as electronic devices that could display personalized data to visitors.
[src:sign-language/1964-new-york-world-s-fair-p02] Some pavilions incorporated personal computers into their exhibits, and many visitors saw touchtone phones for the first time while at the fair.
[src:sign-language/1964-new-york-world-s-fair-p02] Other innovations, such as thermonuclear fusion power plants, undersea hotels, underground houses, jet packs, and Corfam synthetic leather, never became popular.
[src:sign-language/1964-new-york-world-s-fair-p02] Moses predicted the WFC would need to spend $11.6 million to clear Flushing Meadows–Corona Park after the fair closed.
[src:sign-language/1964-new-york-world-s-fair-p02] He recommended the demolition of most of the pavilions.
[src:sign-language/1964-new-york-world-s-fair-p02] By mid-1965, the WFC proposed the preservation of 19 structures, while the remaining pavilions were offered to anyone who could afford to relocate them.
[src:sign-language/1964-new-york-world-s-fair-p02] Steel and Thailand, chose to sell their buildings due to the high cost of demolition, while others sold the contents of their pavilions, and people offered to salvage parts of some buildings.
[src:sign-language/1964-new-york-world-s-fair-p02] Any other buildings had to be demolished within 90 days of the fair's closure.
[src:sign-language/1964-new-york-world-s-fair-p02] Each exhibitor was supposed to have placed money in escrow or posted a bond to cover the demolition costs, but most exhibitors had not done so.
[src:sign-language/1964-new-york-world-s-fair-p02] The WFC feared exhibitors would abandon their pavilions.
[src:sign-language/1964-new-york-world-s-fair-p02] Demolition began the day after the fair closed and the rubble was dumped into Flushing Bay.
[src:sign-language/1964-new-york-world-s-fair-p02] By November, the site was filled with rubbish and rats.
[src:sign-language/1964-new-york-world-s-fair-p02] Scientists temporarily preserved three of the fair's buildings for structural testing.
[src:sign-language/1964-new-york-world-s-fair-p02] The deadline for demolition was extended to December 1966, and by the middle of that year, about 24 structures remained.
[src:sign-language/1964-new-york-world-s-fair-p02] Moses suggested his Triborough Bridge and Tunnel Authority should provide funding to convert the fairground into a park.
[src:sign-language/1964-new-york-world-s-fair-p02] The city government took over Flushing Meadows–Corona Park from the WFC in June 1967.
[src:sign-language/1964-new-york-world-s-fair-p02] Few improvements were made to the park for several years and many of the remaining structures were vandalized.
[src:sign-language/1964-new-york-world-s-fair-p02] According to a 1986 report, the city government had to spend $107 million ($314 million in 2025) to turn the fairground into a park.
[src:sign-language/1964-new-york-world-s-fair-p02] In the 1980s, a 1989 World's Fair was proposed for the site to mark the 25th Anniversary of the 1964 fair, but the proposal was unsuccessful.
[src:sign-language/1964-new-york-world-s-fair-p02] The paths remain almost unchanged into the 21st century.
[src:sign-language/1964-new-york-world-s-fair-p02] Some of the structures from the 1964 World's Fair, including the fair's symbol the Unisphere, remain in Flushing Meadows–Corona Park.
[src:sign-language/1964-new-york-world-s-fair-p02] Near the Unisphere is the Column of Jerash from Jordan's pavilion, a stone bench marking the site of the Vatican pavilion, and a plaque on the site of the Garden of Meditation.
[src:sign-language/1964-new-york-world-s-fair-p02] The New York City Pavilion houses Queens Museum, and the New York Hall of Science is also preserved as a museum.
[src:sign-language/1964-new-york-world-s-fair-p02] The western side of the fairground site includes the Port Authority pavilion, which became the Terrace on the Park banquet hall; the Winston Churchill Tribute, which became an aviary for Queens Zoo; and the Flushing Meadows Carousel.
[src:sign-language/1964-new-york-world-s-fair-p02] The New York State Pavilion is largely unused as of 2024, but its former Theaterama is used by Queens Theatre in the Park.
[src:sign-language/1964-new-york-world-s-fair-p02] The World's Fair Marina along Flushing Bay still operates.
[src:sign-language/1964-new-york-world-s-fair-p02] Other buildings, including the Transportation and Travel and Greyhound pavilions, stayed late into demolition; the Greyhound Pavilion survived until a few months after the park's reopening.
[src:sign-language/1964-new-york-world-s-fair-p02] The United States Pavilion, the Aquacade amphitheater, press building, and the Singer Bowl remained for several years before their demolition.
[src:sign-language/1964-new-york-world-s-fair-p02] Other structures were relocated after the fair closed; among these were the Austria, Christian Science, Denmark, Indonesia, Japan, Malaysia, Mormon, Parker Pen, Spain, Switzerland, Thailand, and Wisconsin pavilions. the Uniroyal Giant Tire and Golden Rondelle Theater.
[src:sign-language/1964-new-york-world-s-fair-p02] In some cases, only parts of buildings were preserved due to the high cost of full preservation.
[src:sign-language/1964-new-york-world-s-fair-p02] The LIRR, Mormon, Socony Mobil, and West Berlin pavilions, as well as the monorail, Poupees des Paris, and the wax museum, were preserved within New York.
[src:sign-language/1964-new-york-world-s-fair-p02] Other objects, including parts of the Hollywood and Ireland pavilions, the Coca-Cola pavilion's carillon, the It's a Small World ride, Progressland carousel, and the Swiss Sky Ride, were sent further afield.
[src:sign-language/1964-new-york-world-s-fair-p02] Some pavilions, such as Clairol's "color carousel" and Sinclair Oil's dinosaur exhibits, became traveling exhibitions.
[src:sign-language/1964-new-york-world-s-fair-p02] Profits from the fair would have been used to improve Flushing Meadows–Corona Park, and many of its restaurants broke even.
[src:sign-language/1964-new-york-world-s-fair-p02] On the fair's closing day, the WFC had $11.58 million in cash.
[src:sign-language/1964-new-york-world-s-fair-p02] Moses anticipated the WFC would not be able to repay the remaining $22.4 million in promissory notes, and the WFC was expecting to default on 60 percent of the bonds it had issued.
[src:sign-language/1964-new-york-world-s-fair-p02] In December 1965, Beame determined the fair had lost $20.1 million in 1964 due to improper management.
[src:sign-language/1964-new-york-world-s-fair-p02] The WFC later agreed to pay noteholders another $4 million in mid-1966, although it struggled to fulfill its obligation to restore the fairground.
[src:sign-language/1964-new-york-world-s-fair-p02] During the late 1960s, the WFC was separately investigated on charges of financial mismanagement regarding the Belgian Village pavilion, and the New York state government opened a racketeering investigation into the fair's construction.
[src:sign-language/1964-new-york-world-s-fair-p02] The city government received $1.5 million in profits from the fair in 1972, following several years of legal disputes.
[src:sign-language/1964-new-york-world-s-fair-p02] The fair recorded a net loss of $21.1 million, and bondholders received back about one-third of their original investments.
[src:sign-language/1964-new-york-world-s-fair-p02] In total, the WFC and other public agencies had spent $83.832 million on permanent improvements to the site during the 1964 fair.
[src:sign-language/1964-new-york-world-s-fair-p02] In part because of the 1964 fair's unprofitability, many industrial exhibitors were reluctant to sponsor major exhibits at the next world's fair, Expo 67 in Montreal, Canada, and two other American cities withdrew proposals for world's fairs in the 1960s and 1970s.
[src:sign-language/1964-new-york-world-s-fair-p02] Citing the 1964 fair, Expo 67's organizers heavily invested in amusement attractions, sought and received BIE approval, and constructed pavilions ahead of schedule.
[src:sign-language/1964-new-york-world-s-fair-p02] Expo 67 officials also sought positive press coverage for their fair, a significant departure from Moses's negative reaction to every perceived criticism.
[src:sign-language/1964-new-york-world-s-fair-p02] Before the fair opened, *The Washington Post* called it a "mixed boon" to New York City because BIE members had boycotted the fair.
[src:sign-language/1964-new-york-world-s-fair-p02] In late 1963, just before the fair opened, an Associated Press reporter called it "a big city cousin to the familiar county fair" and said it was becoming one of the United States' most comprehensive exhibits of industries and businesses.
[src:sign-language/1964-new-york-world-s-fair-p02] A British newspaper called the fair "a great big grown-up Disneyland".
[src:sign-language/1964-new-york-world-s-fair-p02] After the fair's opening, *Life* and *Ebony* magazines called it one of mankind's largest expositions, and *Newsweek* wrote the attractions and pavilions were "hard to resist".
[src:sign-language/1964-new-york-world-s-fair-p02] Several writers criticized the large number of industrial exhibits at the fair, and observers complained about the wastefulness of the pavilions' temporary nature.
[src:sign-language/1964-new-york-world-s-fair-p02] During the second season, *Time* magazine wrote the fair was unsuccessful because of long queues, meager exhibits, high prices, and the overwhelmingly large number of attractions for visitors.
[src:sign-language/1964-new-york-world-s-fair-p02] When the fair closed, a *Wall Street Journal* reporter wrote it had failed because it "lacked coordination, a common purpose that could be transmitted to the community".
[src:sign-language/1964-new-york-world-s-fair-p02] Russell Lynes said the concept of the fair was flawed because instant communication between countries was already possible.
[src:sign-language/1964-new-york-world-s-fair-p02] There was also commentary on the conflicting architectural styles, which were controversial even before the official opening.
[src:sign-language/1964-new-york-world-s-fair-p02] In 1961, John Canaday of *The New York Times* wrote he would be surprised if the fair were not "a mess and disaster architecturally".
[src:sign-language/1964-new-york-world-s-fair-p02] After the fair opened, Ada Louise Huxtable of *The New York Times* wrote the fair was architecturally "grotesque", while other critics criticized the structures as befitting Coney Island or a street fair.
[src:sign-language/1964-new-york-world-s-fair-p02] The critic Vincent Scully Jr., in a *Life* magazine article, wrote: "If This Is Architecture, God Help Us".
[src:sign-language/1964-new-york-world-s-fair-p02] In June 1964, *Time* said the fair had "grace and substance" despite the presence of some "tacky" attractions, a sentiment repeated in *The Atlanta Journal-Constitution*.
[src:sign-language/1964-new-york-world-s-fair-p02] The American Institute of Architects gave awards for excellence in design to several pavilions.
[src:sign-language/1964-new-york-world-s-fair-p02] A *Newsday* reporter described the fair as "both garish and subtle, tawdry and tasteful, ephemeral and lasting".
[src:sign-language/1964-new-york-world-s-fair-p02] After the fair closed, architectural critic Wolf Von Eckardt said the fair was "a frightening image of ourselves" because of its "chaotic" architecture.
[src:sign-language/1964-new-york-world-s-fair-p02] In 1967, *New York Times* reporter Robert Alden wrote the 1964 fair benefited from "participation of private industry on a massive scale" and that more countries were participating in Expo 67.
[src:sign-language/1964-new-york-world-s-fair-p02] Another *Times* writer said in 1989: "The 1964 fair was not as self-conscious a portrayal of the future so much as a display of contemporary American achievements".
[src:sign-language/1964-new-york-world-s-fair-p02] The same year, a *Newsday* reporter wrote the 1964 fair had occurred at a time when audiences were no longer awed by cultural and technological innovations.
[src:sign-language/1964-new-york-world-s-fair-p02] Stern wrote in 1995 the 1964 fair had been so attractive in part because "it was out of place amid the realities of life in the nuclear age".
[src:sign-language/1964-new-york-world-s-fair-p02] Dunlap wrote in 2001 the 1964 fair was still ingrained in the public imagination, even though it had been "a tailfin-tacky celebration of jet-age technological hubris" and an "unhappy final chapter" to Moses's career as New York City's main urban planner.
[src:sign-language/1964-new-york-world-s-fair-p02] Samuel, the fair's motto "peace through understanding" was overshadowed by the fair's focus on profits, and a *Bloomberg* reporter wrote in 2013 the fair had been dominated by corporate exhibitors.
[src:sign-language/1964-new-york-world-s-fair-p02] In the same year, Joseph Tirella wrote although "peace through understanding continues to elude us", the United States had become more ethnically diverse due to the Immigration and Nationality Act of 1965, which was enacted just before the fair ended.
[src:sign-language/1964-new-york-world-s-fair-p02] According to *New York Daily News* in 2012, the remaining structures from the fair "have provided [Flushing Meadows–Corona Park] with some of its most striking structures".
[src:sign-language/1964-new-york-world-s-fair-p02] For the fair's 50th anniversary, *Smithsonian* magazine wrote the fair's "limitless faith in material and social progress" had been counteracted by the social upheaval in the U.S. that took place during the mid-1960s.
[src:sign-language/1964-new-york-world-s-fair-p02] In 2018, *The New York Times* wrote the fair was a showcase for futuristic technology and a place where "foreigners could broadcast their best wares and fairgoers could catch a glimpse into their far-off cultures".
[src:sign-language/1964-new-york-world-s-fair-p02] The fair was credited with increasing tourism in New York City, even before the formal opening.
[src:sign-language/1964-new-york-world-s-fair-p02] The city's hotels and garages were often overcrowded during the fair's 1964 season.
[src:sign-language/1964-new-york-world-s-fair-p02] Broadway theaters recorded increased ticket sales, as did other visitor attractions such as the Empire State Building and Radio City Music Hall.
[src:sign-language/1964-new-york-world-s-fair-p02] Though major department stores and restaurants saw increased business, other merchants reported the fair had not had a measurable effect on their businesses.
[src:sign-language/1964-new-york-world-s-fair-p02] To avoid crowds, many residents left the city during the fair.
[src:sign-language/1964-new-york-world-s-fair-p02] Attendance at local amusement parks declined during the fair and some parks, such as Freedomland U.S.A., permanently closed.
[src:sign-language/1964-new-york-world-s-fair-p02] At the end of the 1964 season, the city's Convention and Visitors Bureau estimated the city had earned $400 million due to the fair.
[src:sign-language/1964-new-york-world-s-fair-p02] *The Christian Science Monitor* wrote in 1965 the fair had only partially benefited the area's economy.
[src:sign-language/1964-new-york-world-s-fair-p02] After the fair ended, *The New York Times* estimated it had increased local restaurant profits by eight percent, while stores in Midtown Manhattan saw their profits increase by approximately four percent.
[src:sign-language/1964-new-york-world-s-fair-p02] The highways leading to the fairground remained in use after the fair's closure, and residential development in Queens increased.
[src:sign-language/1964-new-york-world-s-fair-p02] At the fair's 50th anniversary, a writer for *amNewYork Metro* wrote it helped influence 21st-century technologies and highlighted Flushing Meadows–Corona Park as an attraction in itself.
[src:sign-language/1964-new-york-world-s-fair-p02] The fair helped popularize several consumer products such as Belgian waffles and the Ford Mustang.
[src:sign-language/1964-new-york-world-s-fair-p02] The 1964 World's Fair included several exhibits and technologies that were later included in Disney parks; for example, the Illinois Pavilion's Audio-Animatronic of Abraham Lincoln was so popular Audio-Animatronics were later added to many Disney rides.
[src:sign-language/1964-new-york-world-s-fair-p02] Walt Disney designed exhibits at the World's Fair; It's a Small World, the Progressland carousel, and the Magic Skyway were later incorporated into Disney parks.
[src:sign-language/1964-new-york-world-s-fair-p02] The fair has been the subject of documentary films such as *The 1964 World's Fair* (1996), *After the Fair* (2014), and *Peace Through Understanding: The 1964–65 New York World's Fair*.
[src:sign-language/1964-new-york-world-s-fair-p02] The fair and its structures have been depicted in popular media; for example, the New York State Pavilion and the Unisphere appear in the films *Men in Black* and *Iron Man 2*.
[src:sign-language/1964-new-york-world-s-fair-p02] Historians have created websites and written books about the fair.
[src:sign-language/1964-new-york-world-s-fair-p02] The fair has been the subject of several exhibitions at venues including the Flushing Council on Culture and the Arts, Queens Museum, Flushing Town Hall, and the Long Island Museum of American Art, History, and Carriages.
[src:sign-language/1964-new-york-world-s-fair-p02] The fair's 50th anniversary in 2014 was celebrated with six months of parties, exhibits, and other events across Queens.
[src:sign-language/1964-new-york-world-s-fair-p02] Hobbyists have collected memorabilia from the fair, and several collectors have founded the World's Fair Collectors Society.
[src:sign-language/1964-new-york-world-s-fair-p02] Collectors have preserved objects such as bracelets, medallions, ponchos, purses, and pocketknives.
[src:sign-language/1964-new-york-world-s-fair-p02] The Smithsonian Institution and Queens Museum also own objects from the World's Fair, and there have been efforts to develop a World's Fair museum.
[src:sign-language/abbé-de-l-épée] Charles-Michel de l'Épée was born to a wealthy family in Versailles, the seat of political power in what was then the most powerful kingdom of Europe.
[src:sign-language/abbé-de-l-épée] L'Épée then turned his attention toward charitable services for the poor, and, on one foray into the slums of Paris, he had a chance encounter with two young deaf sisters who communicated using a sign language.
[src:sign-language/abbé-de-l-épée] L'Épée decided to dedicate himself to the education of the deaf, and, in 1760, he founded a school.
[src:sign-language/abbé-de-l-épée] Deaf people were banned by the Catholic Church from receiving communion, but in line with emerging philosophical thought of the time, l'Épée came to believe that deaf people were capable of language and concluded that they should be able to receive the sacraments and thus avoid going to hell.
[src:sign-language/abbé-de-l-épée] He began to develop a system of instruction of the French language and religion.
[src:sign-language/abbé-de-l-épée] In the early 1760s, his shelter became the world's first free school for the deaf, open to the public.
[src:sign-language/abbé-de-l-épée] Though L'Épée's original interest was in religious education, his public advocacy and development of a kind of "Signed French" enabled deaf people to legally defend themselves in court for the first time.
[src:sign-language/abbé-de-l-épée] L'Épée died at the beginning of the French Revolution in 1789, and his tomb is in the Church of Saint Roch in Paris.
[src:sign-language/abbé-de-l-épée] He was succeeded by Roch-Ambroise Cucurron Sicard, who became the new head of the school.
[src:sign-language/abbé-de-l-épée] Two years after L'Épée's death, the National Assembly recognised him as a "Benefactor of Humanity" and declared that deaf people had rights according to the Declaration of the Rights of Man and of the Citizen.
[src:sign-language/abbé-de-l-épée] In 1791, the Institution Nationale des Sourds-Muets à Paris, which L'Épée had founded, began to receive government funding.
[src:sign-language/abbé-de-l-épée] Jacques and then renamed again to its present name: Institut National de Jeunes Sourds de Paris.
[src:sign-language/abbé-de-l-épée] His methods of education have spread around the world, and l'Épée is seen today as one of the founding fathers of deaf education.
[src:sign-language/abbé-de-l-épée] Although he advised his (hearing) teachers to learn the signs (lexicon) for use in instructing their deaf students, he did not use their language in the classroom.
[src:sign-language/abbé-de-l-épée] Instead, he developed an idiosyncratic gestural system using some of this lexicon, combined with other invented signs to represent all the verb endings, articles, prepositions, and auxiliary verbs of the French language.
[src:sign-language/abbé-de-l-épée] In English, L'Épée's system has been known as "Methodical Signs" and "Old Signed French" but is perhaps better translated by the phrase *systematised signs*.
[src:sign-language/abbé-de-l-épée] While L'Épée's system laid the philosophical groundwork for the later developments of Manually Coded Languages such as Signed English, it differed somewhat in execution.
[src:sign-language/abbé-de-l-épée] For example, the word *croire* ("believe") was signed using five separate signs—four with the meanings "know", "feel", "say", and "not see" and one that marked the word as a verb (Lane, 1980:122).
[src:sign-language/abbé-de-l-épée] The word *indéchiffrable* ("unintelligible") was also produced with a chain of five signs: interior-understand-possible-adjective-not.
[src:sign-language/abbé-de-l-épée] However, like Manually Coded Languages, L'Épée's system was cumbersome and unnatural to deaf signers.
[src:sign-language/abbé-de-l-épée] A deaf pupil of the school (and later teacher), Laurent Clerc, wrote that the deaf never used the *signes méthodiques* for communication outside the classroom, preferring their own community language (French Sign Language).
[src:sign-language/abbé-de-l-épée] Although L'Épée reportedly had great success with this educational method, his successes were questioned by critics who thought his students were aping his gestures rather than understanding the meaning.
[src:sign-language/abbé-de-l-épée] At the time of l'Épée's death, there were six schools established around France for deaf children and by 1866, there were fifty-four – all using sign language as the mode of instruction.
[src:sign-language/abbé-de-l-épée] What distinguished L'Épée from educators of the deaf before him, and ensured his place in history, is that he allowed his methods and classrooms to be available to the public and other educators.
[src:sign-language/abbé-de-l-épée] As a result of his openness as much as his successes, his methods would become so influential that their mark is still apparent in deaf education today.
[src:sign-language/abbé-de-l-épée] L'Épée also established teacher-training programmes for foreigners who would take his methods back to their countries and who established numerous deaf schools around the world.
[src:sign-language/abbé-de-l-épée] Laurent Clerc, a deaf pupil of the Paris school, went on to co-found the first school for the deaf in North America and brought with him the sign language that formed the basis of modern American Sign Language (ASL), including the signs of the ASL alphabet.
[src:sign-language/abbé-de-l-épée] Some deaf schools in Germany and the UK that were contemporaries of the Abbé de l'Épée's Paris School used an oralist approach emphasising speech and lip reading, in contrast to his belief in manualism.
[src:sign-language/abbé-de-l-épée] Their methods were closely guarded secrets, and they saw Épée as a rival.
[src:sign-language/abbé-de-l-épée] The oralism vs. manualism debate still rages to this day.
[src:sign-language/abbé-de-l-épée] Oralism is sometimes called the German method, and manualism the French method in reference to those times.
[src:sign-language/abbé-de-l-épée] The Paris school still exists, though it now uses French Sign Language in class rather than Épée's methodical signs.
[src:sign-language/abbé-de-l-épée] Located in rue Saint-Jacques in Paris, it is one of four national deaf schools—the others being in Metz, Chambéry, and Bordeaux.
[src:sign-language/abbé-de-l-épée] Even now, L'Épée is commonly described as the inventor of sign language or as having "taught the deaf to sign".
[src:sign-language/abbé-de-l-épée] In fact, he was taught to sign by the deaf.
[src:sign-language/abbé-de-l-épée] L'Épée categorised and recorded French signs so they could be taught to others in order to be used in education, especially about the Christian faith.
[src:sign-language/abbé-de-l-épée] On 24 November 2018, Google Doodle commemorated his 306th birthday.
[src:sign-language/ascii] ASCII encodes each code-point as a value from 0 to 127 – storable as a seven-bit integer.
[src:sign-language/ascii] Ninety-five code-points are printable, including digits *0* to *9*, lowercase letters *a* to *z*, uppercase letters *A* to *Z*, and commonly used punctuation symbols.
[src:sign-language/ascii] For example, the letter `i` is represented as 105 (decimal).
[src:sign-language/ascii] Also, ASCII specifies 33 non-printing control codes which originated with Teletype devices, most of which are now obsolete.
[src:sign-language/ascii] The control characters that are still commonly used include carriage return, line feed, and tab.
[src:sign-language/ascii] ASCII lacks code-points for characters with diacritical marks and therefore does not directly support terms or names such as résumé, jalapeño, or René.
[src:sign-language/ascii] But, depending on hardware and software support, some diacritical marks can be rendered by overwriting a letter with a backtick (`) or tilde (~).
[src:sign-language/ascii] The Internet Assigned Numbers Authority (IANA) prefers the name **US-ASCII** for this character encoding.
[src:sign-language/ascii] ASCII is the standardisation of a seven-bit teleprinter code developed in part from earlier telegraph codes.
[src:sign-language/ascii] Work on the ASCII standard began in May 1961, when IBM engineer Bob Bemer submitted a proposal to the American Standards Association's (ASA) (now the American National Standards Institute or ANSI) X3.2 subcommittee.
[src:sign-language/ascii] The first edition of the standard was published in 1963, contemporaneously with the introduction of the Teletype Model 33.
[src:sign-language/ascii] It later underwent a major revision in 1967, and several further revisions until 1986.
[src:sign-language/ascii] In contrast to earlier telegraph codes such as Baudot, ASCII was ordered for more convenient collation (especially alphabetical sorting of lists), and added controls for devices other than teleprinters.
[src:sign-language/ascii] ASCII was developed under the auspices of a committee of the American Standards Association (ASA), called the X3 committee, by its X3.2 (later X3L2) subcommittee, and later by that subcommittee's X3.2.4 working group (now INCITS).
[src:sign-language/ascii] The ASA later became the United States of America Standards Institute (USASI) and ultimately became the American National Standards Institute (ANSI).
[src:sign-language/ascii] With the other special characters and control codes filled in, ASCII was published as ASA X3.4-1963, leaving 28 code positions without any assigned meaning, reserved for future standardization, and one unassigned control code.
[src:sign-language/ascii] There was some debate at the time whether there should be more control characters rather than the lowercase alphabet.
[src:sign-language/ascii] The indecision did not last long: during May 1963 the CCITT Working Party on the New Telegraph Alphabet proposed to assign lowercase characters to *sticks* 6 and 7, and International Organization for Standardization TC 97 SC 2 voted during October to incorporate the change into its draft standard.
[src:sign-language/ascii] The X3.2.4 task group voted its approval for the change to ASCII at its May 1963 meeting.
[src:sign-language/ascii] Locating the lowercase letters in *sticks* 6 and 7 caused the characters to differ in bit pattern from the upper case by a single bit, which simplified case-insensitive character matching and the construction of keyboards and printers.
[src:sign-language/ascii] It added the brace and vertical bar characters.
[src:sign-language/ascii] It renamed some control characters – SOM became SOH.
[src:sign-language/ascii] It moved or removed others – RU was removed.
[src:sign-language/ascii] The use of ASCII format for Network Interchange was described in 1969.
[src:sign-language/ascii] That document was formally elevated to an Internet Standard in 2015.
[src:sign-language/ascii] In the X3.15 standard, the X3 committee also addressed how ASCII should be transmitted (least significant bit first) and recorded on perforated tape.
[src:sign-language/ascii] They proposed a 9-track standard for magnetic tape and attempted to deal with some punched card formats.
[src:sign-language/ascii] The X3.2 subcommittee designed ASCII based on the earlier teleprinter encoding systems.
[src:sign-language/ascii] Like other character encodings, ASCII specifies a correspondence between digital bit patterns and character symbols (i.e. graphemes and control characters).
[src:sign-language/ascii] This allows digital devices to communicate with each other and to process, store, and communicate character-oriented information such as written language.
[src:sign-language/ascii] Before ASCII was developed, the encodings in use included 26 alphabetic characters, 10 numerical digits, and from 11 to 25 special graphic symbols.
[src:sign-language/ascii] To include all these, and control characters compatible with the Comité Consultatif International Téléphonique et Télégraphique (CCITT) International Telegraph Alphabet No.
[src:sign-language/ascii] 2 (ITA2) standard of 1932, FIELDATA (1956), and early EBCDIC (1963), more than 64 codes were required for ASCII.
[src:sign-language/ascii] ITA2 was in turn based on Baudot code, the 5-bit telegraph code Émile Baudot invented in 1870 and patented in 1874.
[src:sign-language/ascii] The committee debated the possibility of a shift function (like in ITA2), which would allow more than 64 codes to be represented by a six-bit code.
[src:sign-language/ascii] In a shifted code, some character codes determine choices between options for the following character codes.
[src:sign-language/ascii] It allows compact encoding, but is less reliable for data transmission, as an error in transmitting the shift code typically makes a long part of the transmission unreadable.
[src:sign-language/ascii] The standards committee decided against shifting, and so ASCII required at least a seven-bit code.
[src:sign-language/ascii] The committee considered an eight-bit code, since eight bits (octets) would allow two four-bit patterns to efficiently encode two digits with binary-coded decimal.
[src:sign-language/ascii] However, it would require all data transmission to send eight bits when seven could suffice.
[src:sign-language/ascii] The committee voted to use a seven-bit code to minimize costs associated with data transmission.
[src:sign-language/ascii] Since perforated tape at the time could record eight bits in one position, it also allowed for a parity bit for error checking if desired.
[src:sign-language/ascii] Eight-bit machines (with octets as the native data type) that did not use parity checking typically set the eighth bit to 0.
[src:sign-language/ascii] The code itself was patterned so that most control codes were together and all graphic codes were together, for ease of identification.
[src:sign-language/ascii] The first two so-called *ASCII sticks* (32 positions) were reserved for control characters.
[src:sign-language/ascii] The "space" character had to come before graphics to make sorting easier, so it became position 20hex; for the same reason, many special signs commonly used as separators were placed before digits.
[src:sign-language/ascii] The committee decided it was important to support uppercase 64-character alphabets, and chose to pattern ASCII so it could be reduced easily to a usable 64-character set of graphic codes, as was done in the DEC SIXBIT code (1963).
[src:sign-language/ascii] Lowercase letters were therefore not interleaved with uppercase.
[src:sign-language/ascii] To keep options available for lowercase letters and other graphics, the special and numeric codes were arranged before the letters, and the letter *A* was placed in position 41hex to match the draft of the corresponding British standard.
[src:sign-language/ascii] The digits 0–9 are prefixed with 011, but the remaining 4 bits correspond to their respective values in binary, making conversion with binary-coded decimal straightforward (for example, 5 is encoded to 011*0101*, where 5 is *0101* in binary).
[src:sign-language/ascii] Many of the non-alphanumeric characters were positioned to correspond to their shifted position on typewriters; an important subtlety is that these were based on *mechanical* typewriters, not *electric* typewriters.
[src:sign-language/ascii] Mechanical typewriters followed the *de facto* standard set by the Remington No.
[src:sign-language/ascii] 2 (1878), the first typewriter with a shift key, and the shifted values of `23456789-` were `"#$%_&'()` – early typewriters omitted *0* and *1*, using *O* (capital letter *o*) and *l* (lowercase letter *L*) instead, but `1!` and `0)` pairs became standard once 0 and 1 became common.
[src:sign-language/ascii] Thus, in ASCII `!"#$%` were placed in the second stick, positions 1–5, corresponding to the digits 1–5 in the adjacent stick.
[src:sign-language/ascii] The parentheses could not correspond to *9* and *0*, however, because the place corresponding to *0* was taken by the space character.
[src:sign-language/ascii] This was accommodated by removing `_` (underscore) from *6* and shifting the remaining characters, which corresponded to many European typewriters that placed the parentheses with *8* and *9*.
[src:sign-language/ascii] This discrepancy from typewriters led to bit-paired keyboards, notably the Teletype Model 33, which used the left-shifted layout corresponding to ASCII, differently from traditional mechanical typewriters.
[src:sign-language/ascii] 2, and the `,< .>` pairs were used on some keyboards (others, including the No.
[src:sign-language/ascii] 2, did not shift `,` (comma) or `.` (full stop) so they could be used in uppercase without unshifting).
[src:sign-language/ascii] However, ASCII split the `;:` pair (dating to No.
[src:sign-language/ascii] 2), and rearranged mathematical symbols (varied conventions, commonly `-* =+`) to `:* ;+ -=`.
[src:sign-language/ascii] Some then-common typewriter characters were not included, notably `½ ¼ ¢`, while ^ ` ~ were included as diacritics for international use, and `< >` for mathematical use, together with the simple line characters `\ |` (in addition to common `/`).
[src:sign-language/ascii] The *@* symbol was not used in continental Europe and the committee expected it would be replaced by an accented *À* in the French variation, so the *@* was placed in position 40hex, right before the letter A.
[src:sign-language/ascii] The control codes felt essential for data transmission were the start of message (SOM), end of address (EOA), end of message (EOM), end of transmission (EOT), "who are you?" (WRU), "are you?" (RU), a reserved device control (DC0), synchronous idle (SYNC), and acknowledge (ACK).
[src:sign-language/ascii] These were positioned to maximize the Hamming distance between their bit patterns.
[src:sign-language/ascii] ASCII-code order is also called *ASCIIbetical* order.
[src:sign-language/ascii] Collation of data is sometimes done in this order rather than "standard" alphabetical order (collating sequence).
[src:sign-language/ascii] An intermediate order converts uppercase letters to lowercase before comparing ASCII values.
[src:sign-language/ascii] ASCII reserves the first 32 code points (numbers 0–31 decimal) and the last one (number 127 decimal) for control characters.
[src:sign-language/ascii] These are codes intended to control peripheral devices (such as printers), or to provide meta-information about data streams, such as those stored on magnetic tape.
[src:sign-language/ascii] Despite their name, these code points do not represent printable characters (i.e. they are not characters at all, but signals).
[src:sign-language/ascii] For debugging purposes, "placeholder" symbols (such as those given in ISO 2047 and its predecessors) are assigned to them.
[src:sign-language/ascii] For example, character 0x0A represents the "line feed" function (which causes a printer to advance its paper), and character 8 represents "backspace".
[src:sign-language/ascii] RFC 2822 refers to control characters that do not include carriage return, line feed or white space as non-whitespace control characters.
[src:sign-language/ascii] Except for the control characters that prescribe elementary line-oriented formatting, ASCII does not define any mechanism for describing the structure or appearance of text within a document.
[src:sign-language/ascii] Other schemes, such as markup languages, address page and document layout and formatting.
[src:sign-language/ascii] The original ASCII standard used only short descriptive phrases for each control character.
[src:sign-language/ascii] The ambiguity this caused was sometimes intentional, such as when a character would be used slightly differently on a terminal link or in a data stream.
[src:sign-language/ascii] Probably the most influential single device affecting the interpretation of these characters was the Teletype Model 33 ASR, which was a printing terminal with an available paper tape reader/punch option.
[src:sign-language/ascii] Paper tape was a very popular medium for long-term program storage until the 1980s, less costly and in some ways less fragile than magnetic tape.
[src:sign-language/ascii] In particular, the Teletype Model 33 machine assignments for codes 17 (control-Q, DC1, also known as XON), 19 (control-S, DC3, also known as XOFF), and 127 (delete) became *de facto* standards.
[src:sign-language/ascii] The Model 33 was also notable for taking the description of control-G (code 7, BEL, meaning audibly alert the operator) literally, as the unit contained an actual bell which it rang when it received a BEL character.
[src:sign-language/ascii] When a Teletype 33 ASR equipped with the automatic paper tape reader received a control-S (XOFF, an abbreviation for transmit off), it caused the tape reader to stop; receiving control-Q (XON, transmit on) caused the tape reader to resume.
[src:sign-language/ascii] This so-called flow control technique became adopted by several early computer operating systems as a "handshaking" signal warning a sender to stop transmission because of impending buffer overflow; it persists to this day in many systems as a manual output control technique.
[src:sign-language/ascii] On some systems, control-S retains its meaning, but control-Q is replaced by a second control-S to resume output.
[src:sign-language/ascii] The 33 ASR also could be configured to employ control-R (DC2) and control-T (DC4) to start and stop the tape punch; on some units equipped with this function, the corresponding control character lettering on the keycap above the letter was TAPE and TAPE respectively.
[src:sign-language/ascii] The Teletype could not move its typehead backwards, so it did not have a key on its keyboard to send a BS (backspace).
[src:sign-language/ascii] Instead, there was a key marked RUB OUT that sent code 127 (DEL).
[src:sign-language/ascii] The purpose of this key was to erase mistakes in a manually-input paper tape: the operator had to push a button on the tape punch to back it up, then type the rubout, which punched all holes and replaced the mistake with a character that was intended to be ignored.
[src:sign-language/ascii] Teletypes were commonly used with the less-expensive computers from Digital Equipment Corporation (DEC); these systems had to use what keys were available, and thus the DEL character was assigned to erase the previous character.
[src:sign-language/ascii] Because of this, DEC video terminals (by default) sent the DEL character for the key marked "Backspace" while the separate key marked "Delete" sent an escape sequence; many other competing terminals sent a BS character for the backspace key.
[src:sign-language/ascii] The assumption that no key sent a BS character allowed Ctrl+H to be used for other purposes, such as the "help" prefix command in GNU Emacs.
[src:sign-language/ascii] Many more of the control characters have been assigned meanings quite different from their original ones.
[src:sign-language/ascii] The "escape" character (ESC, code 27), for example, was intended originally to allow sending of other control characters as literals instead of invoking their meaning, an "escape sequence".
[src:sign-language/ascii] This is the same meaning of "escape" encountered in URL encodings, C language strings, and other systems where certain characters have a reserved meaning.
[src:sign-language/ascii] Over time this interpretation has been co-opted and has eventually been changed.
[src:sign-language/ascii] In modern usage, an ESC sent *to* the terminal usually indicates the start of a command sequence, which can be used to address the cursor, scroll a region, set/query various terminal properties, and more.
[src:sign-language/ascii] They are usually in the form of a so-called "ANSI escape code" (often starting with a "Control Sequence Introducer", "CSI", "ESC [") from ECMA-48 (1972) and its successors.
[src:sign-language/ascii] Some escape sequences do not have introducers, like the "Reset to Initial State", "RIS" command "ESC c".
[src:sign-language/ascii] In contrast, an ESC read *from* the terminal is most often used as an out-of-band character used to terminate an operation or special mode, as in the TECO and vi text editors.
[src:sign-language/ascii] In graphical user interface (GUI) and windowing systems, ESC generally causes an application to abort its current operation or to exit (terminate) altogether.
[src:sign-language/ascii] The reapplication of some control characters to new meanings created problems when transferring "plain text" files between systems.
[src:sign-language/ascii] The best example of this is the newline problem in various operating systems.
[src:sign-language/ascii] Teletype machines required that a line of text be terminated with a "carriage return" (to move the printhead to the beginning of the line) followed by a "line feed" (to advance the paper by one line).
[src:sign-language/ascii] The name "carriage return" comes from the fact that, on a manual typewriter, the carriage holding the paper moves while the typebars that strike the ribbon remain stationary.
[src:sign-language/ascii] The entire carriage must be pushed to the right ("returned") in order to position the paper for the next line.
[src:sign-language/ascii] DEC operating systems (OS/8, RT-11, RSX-11, RSTS, TOPS-10, etc.) stored both characters at the end of each line in textual files, as needed by Teletype machines.
[src:sign-language/ascii] When so-called "glass TTYs" were introduced (later called CRTs or "dumb terminals"), they followed the same logic, expecting the same CR and LF characters.
[src:sign-language/ascii] When Gary Kildall created CP/M, he was inspired by some of the command line interface conventions used in DEC's RT-11 operating system.
[src:sign-language/ascii] Until the introduction of IBM PC DOS in 1981, IBM had no influence in this, because their 1970s operating systems used EBCDIC encoding instead of ASCII and they were oriented toward punch-card input and line printer output on which the concept of "carriage return" was meaningless.
[src:sign-language/ascii] IBM's PC DOS (also marketed as MS-DOS by Microsoft) inherited the CRLF convention by virtue of being loosely based on CP/M, and Windows, in turn, inherited it from MS-DOS.
[src:sign-language/ascii] Placing CR and LF at the end of each line in a plain text document or data stream reflects what terminals and printers needed to receive, to display that material.
[src:sign-language/ascii] Multics introduced an innovation: it used only one character (LF), to represent the end of the line in stored files and in data streams.
[src:sign-language/ascii] Upon output, the tty driver converts the LF to CRLF, so files can be printed to a terminal without needing a command to explicitly convert the file format.
[src:sign-language/ascii] Unix and Unix-like systems adopted this design from Multics, as did Amiga systems.
[src:sign-language/ascii] UNIX documents say "newline" or "NL" to refer to the line terminator.
[src:sign-language/ascii] Contrarily, the Radio Shack TRS-80, Apple DOS, Apple ProDOS, and classic Mac OS used a lone carriage return (CR) to terminate lines.
[src:sign-language/ascii] Apple's later operating system, Mac OS X (now called macOS) is based on Unix, so it uses line feed (LF).
[src:sign-language/ascii] To enable communication between all these systems, the Telnet protocol defined a "Network Virtual Terminal" (NVT), wherein a single text format (ASCII with CR-LF line endings) was used for transmission and each system converted to/from its own native representation.
[src:sign-language/ascii] The File Transfer Protocol adopted the Telnet protocol, including the Network Virtual Terminal, for transmitting commands and for transferring textual files (known as "ASCII mode").
[src:sign-language/ascii] The World Wide Web's HTTP uses a modified NVT: the standard allows lone CR and LF characters but requires that each be interpreted as an NVT CRLF.
[src:sign-language/ascii] Complexity arose in network-facing systems that didn't follow the NVT mechanism, such as some version control systems.
[src:sign-language/ascii] Bugs sometimes expose a system's native implementation to other systems on the Internet, causing data corruption.
[src:sign-language/ascii] The PDP-6 monitor, and its PDP-10 successor TOPS-10, used control-Z (SUB) as an end-of-file indication for input from a terminal.
[src:sign-language/ascii] Some operating systems such as CP/M tracked file length only in units of disk blocks, and used control-Z to mark the end of the actual text in the file.
[src:sign-language/ascii] For these reasons, EOF, or end-of-file, was used colloquially and conventionally as a three-letter acronym for control-Z instead of SUBstitute.
[src:sign-language/ascii] The end-of-text character (ETX), also known as control-C, was inappropriate for a variety of reasons, while using control-Z as the control character to end a file is analogous to the letter Z's position at the end of the alphabet, and serves as a very convenient mnemonic aid.
[src:sign-language/ascii] A historically common and still prevalent convention uses the ETX character convention to interrupt and halt a program via an input data stream, usually from a keyboard.
[src:sign-language/ascii] The Unix terminal driver uses the end-of-transmission character (EOT), also known as control-D, to indicate the end of a data stream.
[src:sign-language/ascii] In the C programming language, and in Unix conventions, the null character is used to terminate text strings; such null-terminated strings can be known in abbreviation as ASCIZ or ASCIIZ, where here Z stands for "zero".
[src:sign-language/ascii] Other representations might be used by specialist equipment, for example ISO 2047 graphics or hexadecimal numbers.
[src:sign-language/ascii] At the time of adoption, the codes 20hex to 7Ehex would cause the printing of a visible character (a glyph), and thus were designated "printable characters".
[src:sign-language/ascii] These codes represent letters, digits, punctuation marks, and a few miscellaneous symbols.
[src:sign-language/ascii] There are 95 printable characters in total.
[src:sign-language/ascii] The empty space between words, as produced by the space bar of a keyboard, is character code 20hex.
[src:sign-language/ascii] Since the space character is visible in printed text it considered a "printable character", even though it is unique in having no visible glyph.
[src:sign-language/ascii] It is listed in the printable character table, as per the ASCII standard, instead of in the control character table.
[src:sign-language/ascii] Code 7Fhex corresponds to the non-printable "delete" (DEL) control character and is listed in the control character table.
[src:sign-language/ascii] Earlier versions of ASCII used the up arrow instead of the caret (5Ehex) and the left arrow instead of the underscore (5Fhex).
[src:sign-language/ascii] ASCII was first used commercially during 1963 as a seven-bit teleprinter code for American Telephone & Telegraph's TWX (TeletypeWriter eXchange) network.
[src:sign-language/ascii] TWX originally used the earlier five-bit ITA2, which was also used by the competing Telex teleprinter system.
[src:sign-language/ascii] Bob Bemer introduced features such as the escape sequence.
[src:sign-language/ascii] His British colleague Hugh McGregor Ross helped to popularize this work – according to Bemer, "so much so that the code that was to become ASCII was first called the *Bemer–Ross Code* in Europe".
[src:sign-language/ascii] Because of his extensive work on ASCII, Bemer has been called "the father of ASCII".
[src:sign-language/ascii] On March 11, 1968, US President Lyndon B.
[src:sign-language/ascii] ASCII was the most common character encoding on the World Wide Web until December 2007, when the UTF-8 encoding surpassed it; UTF-8 is backward compatible with ASCII.
[src:sign-language/ascii] As computer technology spread throughout the world, different standards bodies and corporations developed many variations of ASCII to facilitate the expression of non-English languages that used Roman-based alphabets.
[src:sign-language/ascii] One could class some of these variations as "ASCII extensions", although some misuse that term to represent all variants, including those that do not preserve ASCII's character-map in the 7-bit range.
[src:sign-language/ascii] Furthermore, the ASCII extensions have also been mislabelled as ASCII.
[src:sign-language/ascii] From early in its development, ASCII was intended to be just one of several national variants of an international character code standard.
[src:sign-language/ascii] Almost every country needed an adapted version of ASCII, since ASCII suited the needs of only the US and a few other countries.
[src:sign-language/ascii] For example, Canada had its own version that supported French characters.
[src:sign-language/ascii] Many other countries developed variants of ASCII to include non-English letters (e.g. é, ñ, ß, Ł), currency symbols (e.g. £, ¥), etc.
[src:sign-language/ascii] It would share most characters in common, but assign other locally useful characters to several code points reserved for "national use".
[src:sign-language/ascii] ISO/IEC 646, like ASCII, is a 7-bit character set.
[src:sign-language/ascii] It does not make any additional codes available, so the same code points encoded different characters in different countries.
[src:sign-language/ascii] C trigraphs were created to solve this problem for ANSI C, although their late introduction and inconsistent implementation in compilers limited their use.
[src:sign-language/ascii] Many programmers kept their computers on ASCII, so plain-text in Swedish, German etc.
[src:sign-language/ascii] (for example, in e-mail or Usenet) contained "{, }" and similar variants in the middle of words, something those programmers got used to.
[src:sign-language/ascii] For example, a Swedish programmer mailing another programmer asking if they should go for lunch, could get "N{ jag har sm|rg}sar" as the answer, which should be "Nä jag har smörgåsar" meaning "No I've got sandwiches".
[src:sign-language/ascii] In Japan and Korea, still as of the 2020s, a variation of ASCII is used, in which the backslash (5C hex) is rendered as ¥ (a Yen sign, in Japan) or ₩ (a Won sign, in Korea).
[src:sign-language/ascii] This means that, for example, the file path C:\Users\Smith is shown as C:¥Users¥Smith (in Japan) or C:₩Users₩Smith (in Korea).
[src:sign-language/ascii] In Europe, teletext character sets, which are variants of ASCII, are used for broadcast TV subtitles, defined by World System Teletext and broadcast using the DVB-TXT standard for embedding teletext into DVB transmissions.
[src:sign-language/ascii] In the case that the subtitles were initially authored for teletext and converted, the derived subtitle formats are constrained to the same character sets.
[src:sign-language/ascii] Eventually, as 8-, 16-, and 32-bit (and later 64-bit) computers began to replace 12-, 18-, and 36-bit computers as the norm, it became common to use an 8-bit byte to store each character in memory, providing an opportunity for extended, 8-bit relatives of ASCII.
[src:sign-language/ascii] In most cases these developed as true extensions of ASCII, leaving the original character-mapping intact, but adding additional character definitions after the first 128 (i.e., 7-bit) characters.
[src:sign-language/ascii] ASCII itself remained a seven-bit code: the term "extended ASCII" has no official status.
[src:sign-language/ascii] For some countries, 8-bit extensions of ASCII were developed that included support for characters used in local languages (for example, ISCII for India and VISCII for Vietnam).
[src:sign-language/ascii] Even for markets where it was not necessary to add many characters to support additional languages, manufacturers of early home computer systems often developed their own 8-bit extensions of ASCII to include additional characters, such as box-drawing characters, semigraphics, and video game sprites.
[src:sign-language/ascii] Often, these additions also replaced control characters (index 0 to 31, as well as index 127) with even more platform-specific extensions.
[src:sign-language/ascii] In other cases, the extra bit was used for some other purpose, such as toggling inverse video; this approach was used by ATASCII, an extension of ASCII developed by Atari.
[src:sign-language/ascii] Most ASCII extensions are based on ASCII-1967 (the current standard), but some extensions are instead based on the earlier ASCII-1963.
[src:sign-language/ascii] For example, PETSCII, which was developed by Commodore International for their 8-bit systems, is based on ASCII-1963.
[src:sign-language/ascii] Likewise, many Sharp MZ character sets are based on ASCII-1963.
[src:sign-language/ascii] IBM defined code page 437 for the IBM PC, replacing the control characters with graphic symbols such as smiley faces, and mapping additional graphic characters to the upper 128 positions.
[src:sign-language/ascii] Digital Equipment Corporation developed the Multinational Character Set (DEC-MCS) for use in the popular VT220 terminal as one of the first extensions designed more for international languages than for block graphics.
[src:sign-language/ascii] Apple defined Mac OS Roman for the Macintosh and Adobe defined the PostScript Standard Encoding for PostScript; both sets contained "international" letters, typographic symbols and punctuation marks instead of graphics, more like modern character sets.
[src:sign-language/ascii] The ISO/IEC 8859 standard (derived from the DEC-MCS) provided a standard that most systems copied (or at least were based on, when not copied exactly).
[src:sign-language/ascii] A popular further extension designed by Microsoft, Windows-1252 (often mislabeled as ISO-8859-1), added the typographic punctuation marks needed for traditional text printing.
[src:sign-language/ascii] ISO-8859-1, Windows-1252, and the original 7-bit ASCII were the most common character encoding methods on the World Wide Web until 2008, when UTF-8 overtook them.
[src:sign-language/ascii] ISO/IEC 4873 introduced 32 additional control codes defined in the 80–9F hexadecimal range, as part of extending the 7-bit ASCII encoding to become an 8-bit system.
[src:sign-language/ascii] Unicode and the ISO/IEC 10646 Universal Character Set (UCS) have a much wider array of characters and their various encoding forms have begun to supplant ISO/IEC 8859 and ASCII rapidly in many environments.
[src:sign-language/ascii] While ASCII is limited to 128 characters, Unicode and the UCS support more characters by separating the concepts of unique identification (using natural numbers called *code points*) and encoding (to 8-, 16-, or 32-bit binary formats, called UTF-8, UTF-16, and UTF-32, respectively).
[src:sign-language/ascii] ASCII was incorporated into the Unicode (1991) character set as the first 128 symbols, so the 7-bit ASCII characters have the same numeric codes in both sets.
[src:sign-language/ascii] This allows UTF-8 to be backward compatible with 7-bit ASCII, as a UTF-8 file containing only ASCII characters is identical to an ASCII file containing the same sequence of characters.
[src:sign-language/ascii] Even more importantly, forward compatibility is ensured as software that recognizes only 7-bit ASCII characters as special and does not alter bytes with the highest bit set (as is often done to support 8-bit ASCII extensions such as ISO-8859-1) will preserve UTF-8 data unchanged.
[src:sign-language/asl-name-sign] American Sign Language (ASL) has grammar just like any other sign language or spoken language.
[src:sign-language/asl-name-sign] The study of ASL structure dates back to William Stokoe, Dorothy Casterline, and Carl Croneberg in the 1960s.
[src:sign-language/asl-name-sign] Since then, linguists have been describing patterns in ASL responsible for creating meaning at all kinds of levels, from the word, to phrases and sentences and beyond.
[src:sign-language/asl-name-sign] Not all of these linguists ascribe to the same theoretical framework, using various theories, models, and analyses.
[src:sign-language/asl-name-sign] Some analyze the language from a generative linguistics perspective, while others from a cognitive linguistics perspective.
[src:sign-language/asl-name-sign] In ASL morphology, publications have historically categorized morphological processes under two umbrellas: derivational morphology and inflectional morphology.
[src:sign-language/asl-name-sign] Derivational morphology is the process by which new units can be created in a language, and like any other language, this process has been observed in a variety of forms in ASL.
[src:sign-language/asl-name-sign] One form of derivational morphology occurs when a change in movement changes the sign's meaning – often between a noun and a verb.
[src:sign-language/asl-name-sign] This may be done either by reduplicating the movement of the verb if the verb has a single movement, or by restraining (making smaller and faster) the movement of the verb if it already has repeated movement.
[src:sign-language/asl-name-sign] For example, the noun CHAIR is derived from the verb SIT through reduplication.
[src:sign-language/asl-name-sign] Another way of deriving new words in ASL is via the process of compounding, which often differ in meaning from their constituent signs.
[src:sign-language/asl-name-sign] For example, the signs FACE and STRONG compound to create a new sign FACE^STRONG, meaning 'to resemble'.
[src:sign-language/asl-name-sign] Some linguists have analyzed various compounds as a type of suffixation.
[src:sign-language/asl-name-sign] Agent nouns may be derived from verbs by adding the sign, or suffix, AGENT and deleting the final hold of the verb, e.g.
[src:sign-language/asl-name-sign] Superlatives have also been analyzed as created by a formed by suffixation, e.g.
[src:sign-language/asl-name-sign] For example, Ted Supalla's work on ASL verbs of motion analyzed these signs as consisting of many different affixes, articulated simultaneously according to complex grammatical constraints.
[src:sign-language/asl-name-sign] This differs from the concatenative morphology of many spoken languages, which except for suprasegmental features, such as tone, are tightly constrained by the sequential nature of voice sounds.
[src:sign-language/asl-name-sign] Numeral incorporation is another derivational morphological process that has been studied in ASL.
[src:sign-language/asl-name-sign] Certain types of signs, for example, those relating to time and age, may incorporate numbers by assimilating their handshape.
[src:sign-language/asl-name-sign] For example, the word for 'week' has handshape /B/ with the weak hand and /1/ with the active hand; the active hand's handshape may be changed to the handshape of any number up to 9 to indicate that many weeks.
[src:sign-language/asl-name-sign] Some linguists have analyzed this phenomenon as a type of affixation.
[src:sign-language/asl-name-sign] Signs of age, for example, will begin with a touch at the chin.
[src:sign-language/asl-name-sign] They argue that this touch functions as a prefix which completely assimilates with the handshape of the corresponding age number.
[src:sign-language/asl-name-sign] For instance, the word for 'nine' is signed with an /F/ handshape produced ipsilaterally in front of the signer's shoulder.
[src:sign-language/asl-name-sign] The chin-touch in 'nine years old' can be analyzed as an affix, which is then produced with this same /F/ handshape.
[src:sign-language/asl-name-sign] For 'three years old', however, the prefix is made with a 3 handshape.
[src:sign-language/asl-name-sign] Inflectional morphology adds units of language to other words.
[src:sign-language/asl-name-sign] For example, this would be changing 'watch' to 'watches' or 'watching.' In ASL, the sign may remain unchanged as WATCH, or the meaning may change based on non-manual markers (NMM).
[src:sign-language/asl-name-sign] ASL morphology demonstrates reduplication and indexicality as well.
[src:sign-language/asl-name-sign] There are about 20 non-manual modifiers in ASL, which are either adjectival or adverbial.
[src:sign-language/asl-name-sign] Rather than relying on sequential affixes, ASL makes heavy use of simultaneous modification of signs.
[src:sign-language/asl-name-sign] One example of this is found in the aspectual system (see below); another is *numeral incorporation:* There are several families of two-handed signs which require one of the hands to take the handshape of a numeral.
[src:sign-language/asl-name-sign] For example, drawing the dominant hand lengthwise across the palm and fingers of a flat B hand indicates a number of weeks; the dominant hand takes the form of a numeral from one to nine to specify how many weeks.
[src:sign-language/asl-name-sign] There are analogous signs for 'weeks ago' and 'weeks from now', etc., though in practice several of these signs are only found with the lower numerals.
[src:sign-language/asl-name-sign] ASL also has a system of classifiers which may be incorporated into signs.
[src:sign-language/asl-name-sign] These classifiers are moved through sign space to iconically represent the actions of their referents.
[src:sign-language/asl-name-sign] For example, an ILY hand may 'lift off' or 'land on' a horizontal B hand to sign an aircraft taking off or landing; a 3 hand may be brought down on a B hand to sign parking a car; and a G hand may be brought toward a V hand to represent one person approaching two.
[src:sign-language/asl-name-sign] The frequency of classifier use depends greatly on genre, occurring at a rate of 17.7% in narratives but only 1.1% in casual speech and 0.9% in formal speech.
[src:sign-language/asl-name-sign] Frames are a morphological device that may be unique to sign languages (Liddell 2004).
[src:sign-language/asl-name-sign] They are incomplete sets of the features which make up signs, and they combine with existing signs, absorbing features from them to form a derived sign.
[src:sign-language/asl-name-sign] It is the frame which specifies the number and nature of segments in the resulting sign, while the basic signs it combines with lose all but one or two of their original features.
[src:sign-language/asl-name-sign] One, the WEEKLY frame, consists of a simple downward movement.
[src:sign-language/asl-name-sign] It combines with the signs for the days of the week, which then lose their inherent movement.
[src:sign-language/asl-name-sign] For example, 'Monday' consists of an M/O hand made with a circling movement.
[src:sign-language/asl-name-sign] 'MondayWEEKLY' (that is, 'on Mondays') is therefore signed as an M/O hand that drops downward, but without the circling movement.
[src:sign-language/asl-name-sign] A similar ALL DAY frame (a sideward pan) combines with times of the day, such as 'morning' and 'afternoon', which likewise keep their handshape and location but lose their original movement.
[src:sign-language/asl-name-sign] Numeral incorporation (see above) also uses frames.
[src:sign-language/asl-name-sign] However, in ASL frames are most productively utilized for verbal aspect.
[src:sign-language/asl-name-sign] While there is no grammatical tense in ASL, there are numerous verbal aspects.
[src:sign-language/asl-name-sign] These are produced by modulating the verb: through reduplication, by placing the verb in an aspectual frame (see above), or with a combination of these means.
[src:sign-language/asl-name-sign] An example of an aspectual frame is the *unrealized inceptive* aspect ('just about to X'), illustrated here with the verb 'to tell'.
[src:sign-language/asl-name-sign] 'To tell' is an indexical (directional) verb, where the index finger (a G hand) begins with a touch to the chin and then moves outward to point out the recipient of the telling.
[src:sign-language/asl-name-sign] The handshape throughout the sign is whichever is required by the final hold, in this case a G hand.
[src:sign-language/asl-name-sign] The variety of aspects in ASL can be illustrated by the verb 'to be sick', which involves the middle finger of the Y/8 hand touching the forehead, and which can be modified by a large number of frames.
[src:sign-language/asl-name-sign] Several of these involve reduplication, which may but need not be analyzed as part of the frame.
[src:sign-language/asl-name-sign] These modulations readily combine with each other to create yet finer distinctions.
[src:sign-language/asl-name-sign] Not all verbs take all aspects, and the forms they do take will not necessarily be completely analogous to the verb illustrated here.
[src:sign-language/asl-name-sign] Conversely, not all aspects are possible with this one verb.
[src:sign-language/asl-name-sign] Aspect is unusual in ASL in that transitive verbs derived for aspect lose their transitivity.
[src:sign-language/asl-name-sign] Reduplication is also used for expressing verbal number.
[src:sign-language/asl-name-sign] Verbal number indicates that the action of the verb is repeated; in the case of ASL it is apparently limited to transitive verbs, where the motion of the verb is either extended or repeated to cover multiple object or recipient loci.
[src:sign-language/asl-name-sign] (Simple plurality of action can also be conveyed with reduplication, but without indexing any object loci; in fact, such aspectual forms do not allow objects, as noted above.) There are specific dual forms (and for some signers trial forms), as well as plurals.
[src:sign-language/asl-name-sign] If the singular verb uses reduplication, that is lost in the dual and plural forms.
[src:sign-language/asl-name-sign] There are three types of personal name signs in ASL: fingerspelled, arbitrary, and descriptive.
[src:sign-language/asl-name-sign] Fingerspelled names are simply spelled out letter-by-letter.
[src:sign-language/asl-name-sign] Arbitrary name signs only refer to a person's name, while descriptive name signs refer to a person's personality or physical characteristics.
[src:sign-language/asl-name-sign] Once given, names are for life, apart from changing from one of the latter types to an arbitrary sign in childhood.
[src:sign-language/asl-name-sign] Name signs are usually assigned by another member of the Deaf community, and signal inclusion in that community.
[src:sign-language/asl-name-sign] Name signs are not used to address people, as names are in English, but are used only for third-person reference, and usually only when the person is absent.
[src:sign-language/asl-name-sign] The majority of people, probably well in excess of 90%, have arbitrary name signs.
[src:sign-language/asl-name-sign] These are initialized signs: The handshape is the initial of one of the English names of the person, usually the first.
[src:sign-language/asl-name-sign] The sign may occur in neutral space, with a tremble; with a double-tap (as a noun) at one of a limited number of specific locations, such as the side of the chin, the temple, or the elbow; or moving across a location or between two locations, with a single tap at each.
[src:sign-language/asl-name-sign] Single-location signs are simpler in connotation, like English "Vee"; double-location signs are fancier, like English "Veronica".
[src:sign-language/asl-name-sign] Sam Supalla (1992) collected 525 simple arbitrary name signs like these.
[src:sign-language/asl-name-sign] There are two constraints on arbitrary signs.
[src:sign-language/asl-name-sign] That is, it should not duplicate an existing ASL word.
[src:sign-language/asl-name-sign] Second, there should not be more than one person with the name sign in the local community.
[src:sign-language/asl-name-sign] If a person moves to a new community where someone already has their name sign, then the newcomer is obligated to modify theirs.
[src:sign-language/asl-name-sign] This is usually accomplished by compounding the handshape, so that the first tap of the sign takes the initial of the person's first English name, and the second tap takes the initial of their last name.
[src:sign-language/asl-name-sign] There are potentially thousands of such compound-initial signs.
[src:sign-language/asl-name-sign] Descriptive name signs are not initialized, but rather use non-core ASL signs.
[src:sign-language/asl-name-sign] They tend to be assigned and used by children, rather like "Blinky" in English.
[src:sign-language/asl-name-sign] Parents do not give such names to their children, but most Deaf people do not have deaf parents and are assigned their name sign by classmates in their first school for the deaf.
[src:sign-language/asl-name-sign] At most 10% of Deaf people retain such name signs into adulthood..
[src:sign-language/asl-name-sign] Arbitrary name signs became established very early in the history of ASL.
[src:sign-language/asl-name-sign] Descriptive name signs refer to a person's appearance or personality.
[src:sign-language/asl-name-sign] The two systems, arbitrary and descriptive, are sometimes combined, usually for humorous purposes.
[src:sign-language/asl-name-sign] Hearing people learning ASL are also often assigned combined name signs.
[src:sign-language/asl-name-sign] This is not traditional for Deaf people.
[src:sign-language/asl-name-sign] Sometimes people with very short English names, such as "Ann" or "Lee", or ones that flow easily, such as "Larry", may never acquire a name sign, but may instead be referred to with finger-spelling.
[src:sign-language/asl-name-sign] Non-Manual Markers (NMM), or Non-Manual Signals (NMS) are communication methods not found in the hands.
[src:sign-language/asl-name-sign] They typically consist of facial expressions and body language.
[src:sign-language/asl-name-sign] NMMs can change the grammar of a sentence.
[src:sign-language/asl-name-sign] Not every sign uses non-manual markers, but for many others, these markers determine what sign is being produced.
[src:sign-language/asl-name-sign] Some examples of non-manual markers would be the shifting of shoulders, the lowering or raising of eyebrows, a head nod or shake, scrunching of the nose, pursing of the lips, or an open mouth.
[src:sign-language/asl-name-sign] NMMs are important for indicating if a question is being asked.
[src:sign-language/asl-name-sign] For *WH-* questions, the eyebrows are lowered, and for *YES/NO* questions, the eyebrows are raised.
[src:sign-language/asl-name-sign] It is hard to indicate if a question is being asked otherwise without facial indicators.
[src:sign-language/asl-name-sign] Another example would be between *I UNDERSTAND* and *I DON'T UNDERSTAND*.
[src:sign-language/asl-name-sign] The sign for this is the same; the hand is held up near the forehead with the palm facing the self.
[src:sign-language/asl-name-sign] If the person is nodding and has their eyebrows raised, it means *I UNDERSTAND*.
[src:sign-language/asl-name-sign] If they are shaking their head with eyebrows lowered, it means *I DON'T UNDERSTAND*.
[src:sign-language/asl-name-sign] Understanding ASL grammar requires understanding the difference between a signer's dominant and non-dominant hand.
[src:sign-language/asl-name-sign] If a person is right-handed, then their right hand is their dominant hand, and their left hand is their non-dominant hand.
[src:sign-language/asl-name-sign] Almost all signs are completed with the more active, dominant hand, while the non-dominant hand serves as a base.
[src:sign-language/asl-name-sign] For signs requiring two hands, the dominant hand performs more of the active component.
[src:sign-language/asl-name-sign] ASL is a subject–verb–object (SVO) language.
[src:sign-language/asl-name-sign] However, OSV is also an accepted sentence form.
[src:sign-language/asl-name-sign] The default SVO word order is sometimes altered by processes including topicalization and null elements.
[src:sign-language/asl-name-sign] This is marked either with non-manual signals like eyebrow or body position, or with prosodic marking such as pausing.
[src:sign-language/asl-name-sign] These non-manual grammatical markings (such as eyebrow movement or head-shaking) may optionally spread over the c-command domain of the node which it is attached to.
[src:sign-language/asl-name-sign] However, ASL is a pro-drop language, and when the manual sign that a non-manual grammatical marking is attached to is omitted, the non-manual marking obligatorily spreads over the c-command domain.
[src:sign-language/asl-name-sign] The full sentence structure in ASL is [topic] [subject] verb [object] [subject–pronoun–tag].
[src:sign-language/asl-name-sign] Topics and *tags* are both indicated with non-manual features, and both give a great deal of flexibility to ASL word order.
[src:sign-language/asl-name-sign] Within a noun phrase, the word order is noun–number and noun–adjective.
[src:sign-language/asl-name-sign] ASL does not have a copula (linking 'to be' verb).
[src:sign-language/asl-name-sign] In addition to its basic topic–comment structure, ASL typically places an adjective after a noun, though it may occur before the noun for stylistic purposes.
[src:sign-language/asl-name-sign] Numerals also occur after the noun, a very rare pattern among oral languages.
[src:sign-language/asl-name-sign] Adverbs, however, occur before the verbs.
[src:sign-language/asl-name-sign] Most of the time adverbs are simply the same sign as an adjective, distinguished by the context of the sentence.
[src:sign-language/asl-name-sign] When the scope of the adverb is the entire clause, as in the case of time, it comes before the topic.
[src:sign-language/asl-name-sign] ASL makes heavy use of time-sequenced ordering, meaning that events are signed in the order in which they occur.
[src:sign-language/asl-name-sign] For example, for *I was late to class last night because my boss handed me a huge stack of work after lunch yesterday,* one would sign 'YESTERDAY LUNCH FINISH, BOSS GIVE-me WORK BIG-STACK, NIGHT CLASS LATE-me'.
[src:sign-language/asl-name-sign] In stories, however, ordering is malleable, since one can choose to sequence the events either in the order in which they occurred or in the order in which one found out about them.
[src:sign-language/asl-name-sign] It has been claimed that tense in ASL is marked adverbially, and that ASL lacks a separate category of tense markers.
[src:sign-language/asl-name-sign] (1992, 1995) argue that "Tense" (T) is indeed a distinct category of syntactic head, and that the T node can be occupied either by a modal (e.g.
[src:sign-language/asl-name-sign] Aspect may be marked either by verbal inflection or by separate lexical items.
[src:sign-language/asl-name-sign] As noted above, in ASL aspectually marked verbs cannot take objects.
[src:sign-language/asl-name-sign] To deal with this, the object must be known from context so that it does not need to be further specified.
[src:sign-language/asl-name-sign] It may be used as the topic of the utterance at hand.
[src:sign-language/asl-name-sign] Of these two strategies, the first is the more common.
[src:sign-language/asl-name-sign] A topic sets off background information that will be discussed in the following main clause.
[src:sign-language/asl-name-sign] Topicalization is used productively in ASL and often results in surface forms that do not follow the basic SVO word order.
[src:sign-language/asl-name-sign] In order to non-manually mark topics, the eyebrows are raised and the head is tilted back during the production of a topic.
[src:sign-language/asl-name-sign] The head is often lowered toward the end of the sign, and sometimes the sign is followed rapidly nodding the head.
[src:sign-language/asl-name-sign] Another way topics may be signed is by shifting the body.
[src:sign-language/asl-name-sign] The signer may use the space on one side of his/her body to sign the topic, and then shifts to the other side for the rest of the sentence.
[src:sign-language/asl-name-sign] ASL utterances do not require topics, but their use is extremely common.
[src:sign-language/asl-name-sign] They are used for purposes of information flow, to set up referent loci (see above), and to supply objects for verbs which are grammatically prevented from taking objects themselves (see below).
[src:sign-language/asl-name-sign] However, people tend to want to set up the object of their concern first and then discuss what happened to it.
[src:sign-language/asl-name-sign] There are three types of non-manual topic markers, all of which involve raised eyebrows.
[src:sign-language/asl-name-sign] The three types of non-manual topic markers are used with different types of topics and in different contexts, and the topic markings cannot spread over other elements in the utterance.
[src:sign-language/asl-name-sign] Topics can be moved from and remain null in the main clause of an utterance, or topics can be base-generated and either be co-referential to either the subject or object in the main clause or be related to the subject of object by a semantic property.
[src:sign-language/asl-name-sign] The first type of non-manual marking, topic marking 1 (tm1), is only used with a moved topic.
[src:sign-language/asl-name-sign] Tm1 is characterized by raised eyebrows, widened eyes, and head tilted backwards.
[src:sign-language/asl-name-sign] At the end of the sign the head moves down and there is a pause, often with an eye blink, before the sentence is continued.
[src:sign-language/asl-name-sign] Topic marking 2 (tm2) and topic marking 3 (tm3) are both used with base-generated topics.
[src:sign-language/asl-name-sign] Tm2 is characterized by raised eyebrows, widened eyes, and the head tilted backwards and to the side.
[src:sign-language/asl-name-sign] Toward the end of the sign the head moves forward and to the opposite side, and there is a pause and often an eye blink before continuing.
[src:sign-language/asl-name-sign] For tm3 the eyebrows are raised and the eyes are opened wide, the head starts tilted down and jerks up and down, the lips are opened and raised, and the head is nodded rapidly a few times before pausing and continuing the sentence.
[src:sign-language/asl-name-sign] Although both tm2 and tm3 accompany base-generated topics, they are used in different contexts.
[src:sign-language/asl-name-sign] Tm2 is used to introduce new information and change the topic of a conversation to something that the signer is going to subsequently characterize, while tm3 is used to introduce new information that the signer believes is already known by his/her interlocutor.
[src:sign-language/asl-name-sign] Tm2 may be used with any base-generated topic, whereas only topics that are co-referential with an argument in the sentence may be marked with tm3.
[src:sign-language/asl-name-sign] ASL sentences may have up to two marked topics.
[src:sign-language/asl-name-sign] Possible combinations of topic types are two tm2 topics, two tm3 topics, tm2 preceding tm1, tm3 preceding tm1, and tm2 preceding tm3.
[src:sign-language/asl-name-sign] Sentences with these topic combinations in the opposite orders or with two tm1 topics are considered ungrammatical by native signers.
[src:sign-language/asl-name-sign] Relative clauses are signaled by tilting back the head and raising the eyebrows and upper lip.
[src:sign-language/asl-name-sign] This is done during the performance of the entire clause.
[src:sign-language/asl-name-sign] where the brackets here indicate the duration of the non-manual features.
[src:sign-language/asl-name-sign] If the sign 'recently' were made without these features, it would lie outside the relative clause, and the meaning would change to "the dog which chased the cat recently came home".
[src:sign-language/asl-name-sign] Negated clauses may be signaled by shaking the head during the entire clause.
[src:sign-language/asl-name-sign] A topic, however, cannot be so negated; the headshake can only be produced during the production of the main clause.
[src:sign-language/asl-name-sign] In addition, in many communities, negation is put at the end of the clause, unless there is a wh- question word.
[src:sign-language/asl-name-sign] For example, the sentence, "I thought the movie was not good," could be signed as, "BEFORE MOVIE ME SEE, THINK WHAT?
[src:sign-language/asl-name-sign] There are two manual signs that negate a sentence, NOT and NONE, which are accompanied by a shake of the head.
[src:sign-language/asl-name-sign] There are three types of questions with different constructions in ASL: wh- questions, yes/no questions, and rhetorical questions.
[src:sign-language/asl-name-sign] Non-manual grammatical markings are grammatical and semantic features that do not include the use of hands.
[src:sign-language/asl-name-sign] They can include mouth shape, eye gazes, facial expressions, body shifting, head tilting, and eyebrow raising.
[src:sign-language/asl-name-sign] Non-manual grammatical markings can also aid in identifying sentence type, which is especially relevant to our discussion of different types of interrogatives.
[src:sign-language/asl-name-sign] Wh-questions can be formed in a variety of ways in ASL.
[src:sign-language/asl-name-sign] The wh-word can appear solely at the end of the sentence, solely at the beginning of the sentence, at both the beginning and end of the sentence (see section 4.4.2.1 on 'double-occurring wh-words', or in situ (i.e. where the wh-word is in the sentence structure before movement occurs)).
[src:sign-language/asl-name-sign] Manual wh-signs are also accompanied by a non-manual grammatical marking (see section 4.4.1), which can include a variety of features.
[src:sign-language/asl-name-sign] This non-manual grammatical marking can spread optionally over the entire wh-phrase or just a small part.
[src:sign-language/asl-name-sign] Some languages have very few wh-words, where context and discourse are sufficient to elicit the information that one needs.
[src:sign-language/asl-name-sign] ASL has many different wh-words, with certain wh-words having multiple variations.
[src:sign-language/asl-name-sign] A list of the wh-words of ASL can be found below.
[src:sign-language/asl-name-sign] As mentioned above, ASL possesses wh-questions with word initial placement, word final placement, in situ structure, but the most unique style of wh-word occurrence in ASL is where the wh-word occurs twice, copied in final position.
[src:sign-language/asl-name-sign] This doubling can be seen in the table below.
[src:sign-language/asl-name-sign] This doubling provides a useful template to analyze two separate analyses about whether wh-words move rightward or leftward in ASL.
[src:sign-language/asl-name-sign] While some researchers argue for rightward movement in wh- questions such as Aarons and Neidle, others, including Petronio and Lillo-Martin, have argued that ASL has leftward movement and wh- words that appear to the right of the clause move by other processes.
[src:sign-language/asl-name-sign] Both analyses agree upon the fact that there is wh-movement present in these interrogative phrases, but it is a matter of what direction the wh-movement is moving in that causes controversy.
[src:sign-language/asl-name-sign] The leftward movement analysis is congruent with cross-linguistic data that wh-movement is always leftward.
[src:sign-language/asl-name-sign] It can be seen as the less controversial of the two proposals.
[src:sign-language/asl-name-sign] The main arguments presented by the Leftward Wh-movement analysis are: That the spec-CP is on the left, that the wh-movement is leftward, and that the final wh-word in a sentence is a base-generated double.
[src:sign-language/asl-name-sign] This is illustrated in the syntax tree located to the right of this paragraph.
[src:sign-language/asl-name-sign] Arguments for leftward movement are based on the facts that if wh-movement in ASL were rightward, ASL would be an exception to cross-linguistic generalizations that wh-movement is leftward.
[src:sign-language/asl-name-sign] It has also been hypothesized that wh-elements cannot be topicalized, as topicalized elements must be presupposed and interrogatives are not.
[src:sign-language/asl-name-sign] This would be detrimental to the rightward analysis, as they are analyzing the doubled wh-word as a 'base generated topic'.
[src:sign-language/asl-name-sign] The rightward movement analysis is a newer, more abstract argument of how wh-movement occurs in ASL.
[src:sign-language/asl-name-sign] The main arguments for rightward movement begin by analyzing spec-CP as being on the right, the wh-movement as being rightward, and as the initial wh-word as a base-generated topic.
[src:sign-language/asl-name-sign] This can be seen in the syntax tree on the right.
[src:sign-language/asl-name-sign] One of the rightward movement analysis' main arguments is in regards to the non-manual grammatical markings, and their optional spreading over the sentence.
[src:sign-language/asl-name-sign] In ASL the use of non-manual grammatical markings is optional depending on the type of wh-question being asked.
[src:sign-language/asl-name-sign] In the rightward analysis both partial and full spreading of non-manual grammatical markers can be accounted for due to the association with the +WH feature over its c-command domain.
[src:sign-language/asl-name-sign] In the leftward analysis, the partial or full spreading of non manual grammatical markings cannot be accounted for in this same way.
[src:sign-language/asl-name-sign] The leftward movement analysis requires wh-marking to extend over the entirety of the question, regardless (which is not what is attested in ASL).
[src:sign-language/asl-name-sign] In spoken language Yes/no questions will oftentimes differ in their word order from the statement form.
[src:sign-language/asl-name-sign] In ASL, yes/no questions are marked by the non-manual grammatical markings (as discussed in section 4.4.1).
[src:sign-language/asl-name-sign] This eyebrow raise, slight tilt of the head and lean forward are what indicate that a yes/no question is being asked, without any change in word order from the statement form.
[src:sign-language/asl-name-sign] There is speculation amongst linguists that these non-manual grammatical markings that indicate a yes/no questions are similar to the question intonation of spoken languages.
[src:sign-language/asl-name-sign] Yes/no questions differ from wh-questions as they do not differ in word order from the original statement form of the sentence, whereas wh-questions do.
[src:sign-language/asl-name-sign] As well, in yes/no questions, the non-manual marking must be used over the whole utterance in order for it to be judged as a statement opposed to a question.
[src:sign-language/asl-name-sign] The yes/no question is the same word order as the statement form of the sentence, with the addition of non-manual grammatical markings.
[src:sign-language/asl-name-sign] Non-manual grammatical markings are also used for rhetorical questions, which are questions that do not intend to elicit an answer.
[src:sign-language/asl-name-sign] To distinguish the non-manual marking for rhetorical questions from that of yes/no questions, the body is in a neutral position opposed to tilted forward, and the head is tilted in a different way than in yes/no questions.
[src:sign-language/asl-name-sign] Rhetorical questions are much more common in ASL than in English.
[src:sign-language/asl-name-sign] [I LIKE]NEGATIVE [WHAT?]RHETORICAL, GARLIC.
[src:sign-language/asl-name-sign] This strategy is commonly used instead of signing the word 'because' for clarity or emphasis.
[src:sign-language/asl-name-sign] PASTA I EAT ENJOY TRUE [WHY?]RHETORICAL, ITALIAN I.
[src:sign-language/asl-name-sign] In ASL signers set up regions of space (loci) for specific referents (see above); these can then be referred to indexically by pointing at those locations with pronouns and indexical verbs.
[src:sign-language/asl-name-sign] That is, they point to their referent, or to a locus representing their referent.
[src:sign-language/asl-name-sign] If the referent is not physically present, the speaker identifies the referent and then points to a location (the *locus)* in the sign space near their body.
[src:sign-language/asl-name-sign] This locus can then be pointed at to refer to the referent.
[src:sign-language/asl-name-sign] Theoretically, any number of loci may be set up, as long as the signer and recipient remember them all, but in practice, no more than eight loci are used.
[src:sign-language/asl-name-sign] Meier 1990 demonstrates that only two grammatical persons are distinguished in ASL: First person and non-first person, as in Damin.
[src:sign-language/asl-name-sign] Both persons come in several numbers as well as with signs such as 'my' and 'by myself'.
[src:sign-language/asl-name-sign] Meier provides several arguments for believing that ASL does not formally distinguish second from third person.
[src:sign-language/asl-name-sign] For example, when pointing to a person that is physically present, a pronoun is equivalent to either 'you' or '(s)he' depending on the discourse.
[src:sign-language/asl-name-sign] There is nothing in the sign itself, nor in the direction of eye gaze or body posture, that can be relied on to make this distinction.
[src:sign-language/asl-name-sign] That is, the same formal sign can refer to any of several second or third persons, which the indexic nature of the pronoun makes clear.
[src:sign-language/asl-name-sign] In English, indexic uses also occur, as in 'I need *you* to go to the store and *you* to stay here', but not so ubiquitously.
[src:sign-language/asl-name-sign] In contrast, several first-person ASL pronouns, such as the plural possessive ('our'), look different from their non-first-person equivalents, and a couple of pronouns do not occur in the first person at all, so first and non-first persons are formally distinct.
[src:sign-language/asl-name-sign] Personal pronouns have separate forms for singular ('I' and 'you/(s)he') and plural ('we' and 'you/they').
[src:sign-language/asl-name-sign] These have possessive counterparts: 'my', 'our', 'your/his/her', 'your/their'.
[src:sign-language/asl-name-sign] In addition, there are pronoun forms which incorporate numerals from two to five ('the three of us', 'the four of you/them', etc.), though the dual pronouns are slightly idiosyncratic in form *(i.e.,* they have a K rather than 2 handshape, and the wrist nods rather than circles).
[src:sign-language/asl-name-sign] These numeral-incorporated pronouns have no possessive equivalents.
[src:sign-language/asl-name-sign] Also among the personal pronouns are the 'self' forms ('by myself', 'by your/themselves', etc.).
[src:sign-language/asl-name-sign] These only occur in the singular and plural (there is no numeral incorporation), and are only found as subjects.
[src:sign-language/asl-name-sign] They have derived emphatic and 'characterizing' forms, with modifications used for derivation rather like those for verbal aspect.
[src:sign-language/asl-name-sign] The 'characterizing' pronoun is used when describing someone who has just been mentioned.
[src:sign-language/asl-name-sign] It only occurs as a non-first-person singular form.
[src:sign-language/asl-name-sign] Finally, there are formal pronouns used for honored guests.
[src:sign-language/asl-name-sign] These occur as singular and plural in the non-first person, but only as singular in the first person.
[src:sign-language/asl-name-sign] ASL is a pro-drop language, which means that pronouns are not used when the referent is obvious from context and is not being emphasized.
[src:sign-language/asl-name-sign] Within ASL there is a class of indexical (often called 'directional') verbs.
[src:sign-language/asl-name-sign] These include the signs for 'see', 'pay', 'give', 'show', 'invite', 'help', 'send', 'bite', etc.
[src:sign-language/asl-name-sign] These verbs include an element of motion that indexes one or more referents, either physically present or set up through the referent locus system.
[src:sign-language/asl-name-sign] If there are two loci, the first indicates the subject and the second the object, direct or indirect depending on the verb, reflecting the basic word order of ASL.
[src:sign-language/asl-name-sign] For example, 'give' is a bi-indexical verb based on a flattened M/O handshape.
[src:sign-language/asl-name-sign] For 'I give you', the hand moves from myself toward you; for 'you give me', it moves from you to me.
[src:sign-language/asl-name-sign] The verb 'to be in pain' (index fingers pointed at each other and alternately approaching and separating) is signed at the location of the pain (head for headache, cheek for toothache, abdomen for stomachache, etc.).
[src:sign-language/asl-name-sign] This is normally done in relation to the signer's own body, regardless of the person feeling the pain, but may take also use the locus system, especially for body parts which are not normally part of the sign space, such as the leg.
[src:sign-language/asl-name-sign] There are also spatial verbs such as put-up and put-below, which allow signers to specify where things are or how they moved them around.
[src:sign-language/asl-phabet] Like SignFont and Stokoe notation, ASL-phabet is a phonemic script, but it has been simplified to the point where there is some ambiguity, that is, one symbol can represent more than one phonemic element (handshape, location or movement).
[src:sign-language/asl-phabet] For example, whereas SignFont has 25 letters encoding types of movement, and Stokoe notation has 24, ASL-phabet has just 5.
[src:sign-language/asl-phabet] This can result in homographs (more than one sign spelled the same way).
[src:sign-language/asl-phabet] All together, ASL-phabet has 22 letters for handshape, 5 for location, and 5 for movement.
[src:sign-language/asl-phabet] They are written in that order, left-to-right, with the possibility for several letters of each type, such as two handshape letters for a two-handed sign.
[src:sign-language/asl-phabet] Like Stokoe notation (but unlike SignFont), the ASL-phabet does not provide symbols for facial expressions, mouthing, and other aspects of sign language structure, which may make it hard to use for extended text.
[src:sign-language/asl-phabet] However, it is sufficient to look up ASL words in an ASL–English dictionary.
[src:sign-language/aslwrite] Its core components are digits, locatives, marks and movements which are written in a fairly rigid order (though in a fairly flexible configuration) from left to right.
[src:sign-language/aslwrite] The order of the writing is from left to right, top to bottom, with locatives or certain marks often beginning words.
[src:sign-language/aslwrite] Sentences are ended by the full stop mark ().
[src:sign-language/aslwrite] Questions in written ASL are denoted by eyebrow marks bounding the question not unlike Spanish's "¿ ?." Question words or wh-questions in ASL can also form the interrogative.
[src:sign-language/aslwrite] There are in total 105 characters in ASLwrite with 67 digits, five diacritic marks, twelve locatives, sixteen extramanual marks and five movement marks.
[src:sign-language/aslwrite] Since its creation, it has evolved to include more digits, locatives, movements and marks as well as modify those already present.
[src:sign-language/aslwrite] si5s, a system built from SignWriting, was first proposed by Robert Arnold in his 2007 Gallaudet thesis *A Proposal of the Written System for ASL*.
[src:sign-language/aslwrite] The ASLwrite community split from Arnold upon his decision to maintain si5s as a private venture with ASLized after the publication of his and Adrean Clark's book *How to Write American Sign Language*.
[src:sign-language/aslwrite] Aside from the small, but dedicated, Facebook group of around 470 in July 2023, ASLwrite is rarely used outside such online spaces.
[src:sign-language/aslwrite] However, one of the most popular online ASL dictionaries, HandSpeak, has begun to incorporate ASLwrite as the primary written component of ASL definitions.
[src:sign-language/aslwrite] ASLwrite is a somacheirographic system meaning that it represents the body (Greek: σῶμα *sôma* 'body') and hands (Greek: χείρ *kheír* 'hand') and relays phonemic information.
[src:sign-language/aslwrite] However, it also incorporates logographs (questioning marks) and is featural.
[src:sign-language/aslwrite] The general principle is to capture a single ASL word per segment, from left to right, registering non-manual feature(s), location(s), handshape(s), movement(s) and general orientation.
[src:sign-language/aslwrite] It imagines the writer/speaker is looking down at their hands or viewing words from the profile such that words can be made either as if seen from straight-on or from one's profile.
[src:sign-language/aslwrite] The digibet captures handshape information as well as orientation, movement and some locations.
[src:sign-language/aslwrite] Locatives are characters that capture location, though handshape diacritics like *edge* do capture some locations such as edge of palm.
[src:sign-language/aslwrite] Diacritics, such as movements, modify handshapes and can indicate small movements or small orientations.
[src:sign-language/aslwrite] Movements themselves are fairly flexible in their shapes and orientations, which makes digitising this script difficult.
[src:sign-language/aslwrite] Frontal or profile locatives – Captures the same location information, just from two perspectives.
[src:sign-language/aslwrite] An example (seen on the right) is the shoulder locative is either a shoulder frontal locative that is written above or below the handshape(s).
[src:sign-language/aslwrite] Handshapes – Can be written before or after the locative.
[src:sign-language/aslwrite] A handshape can be oriented in 360° depending on its location and is written at the end of its movement path if there is one.
[src:sign-language/aslwrite] Each handshape present is written, and when more than one handshape (of one hand) is written, a movement must be present.
[src:sign-language/aslwrite] Movements – Larger movements or movements that affect multiple handshapes.
[src:sign-language/aslwrite] When a handshape changes without overt movement, the handshapes are written left-to-right with a single movement below, similar to an underline.
[src:sign-language/aslwrite] Non-manual & punctuation marks – These are questioning marks such as *why*, *who*, *how* and *how*.
[src:sign-language/aslwrite] The digibet is composed of handshapes called digits that are modified by diacritics and movements.
[src:sign-language/aslwrite] It shares 23 handshapes with ASL's manual alphabet.
[src:sign-language/aslwrite] Digits are grouped together by features such as +thumb/-thumb or +closed/-closed.
[src:sign-language/aslwrite] In practise, there are 67 digits in ASLwrite's digibet, though that number is growing as new digits are added representing diverse handshapes.
[src:sign-language/aslwrite] Moreover, other languages may adopt this system which would add increasingly more digits.
[src:sign-language/aslwrite] There are five diacritics, of which one is a movement diacritic.
[src:sign-language/aslwrite] Movements are flexible and thus hard to capture in a digital or non-handwritten fashion.
[src:sign-language/aslwrite] The movements are diverse and aim to capture the movements of the hands, arms and body.
[src:sign-language/aslwrite] There are three points – an **endpoint**, a **firmpoint** and a **contactpoint** –, an **orbit mark**, a **steering** and a **crank mark** as well as the movement mark or line.
[src:sign-language/aslwrite] The movement line follows the path of the hand(s) and can be as clean (e.g., – or | ) or as erratic as possible.
[src:sign-language/aslwrite] The points denote the end of a handshape's path and the degree to which the motion is made.
[src:sign-language/aslwrite] A contactpoint denotes an imaginary or in-the-air point with the contactpoint ending at a location and noted as being a firm ending with the firmpoint.
[src:sign-language/aslwrite] The orbit mark indicates a central "point" around which the handshapes orbit; for orbital paths cut short, one would use a steering mark, and for parallel cranking motions, the crank mark would be used.
[src:sign-language/aslwrite] The locatives are characters that denote a specific location on or near the signer's body.
[src:sign-language/aslwrite] They are presented from a face-on and side-view.
[src:sign-language/aslwrite] The two sub-classifications are **frontal** and **profile locatives**.
[src:sign-language/aslwrite] Non-manual marks vary quite significantly and can only be placed at the beginning or end of words or phrases.
[src:sign-language/aslwrite] **Eyebrow marks** are denoted before and after the word(s) in question thus bounding the words that are modified by eyebrow marks.
[src:sign-language/aslwrite] They are called: **Raised (), Knit, Wan, Slanted** and **Squint**.
[src:sign-language/aslwrite] Questioning marks exist in ASL as logographs that denote ASL's wh-questions such as WHO or FOR-FOR.
[src:sign-language/aslwrite] They are placed after a closed word's or phrase's second eyebrow mark and can exist as an entire sentence alone.
[src:sign-language/aslwrite] Mouth marks are characters that relay what action the mouth is doing.
[src:sign-language/aslwrite] It is placed inside the first eyebrow mark.
[src:sign-language/aslwrite] Body movements are non-manual, non-facial features such as **shoulder shift ()** or **head nod**.
[src:sign-language/aslwrite] They, as well as **nose crinkle ()**, stand alone and can be inserted anywhere, inside and outside of eyebrow-marked phrases.
[src:sign-language/aslwrite] means *Yes?* in ASL composed of , , and where the raised eyebrow marks at the beginning and the end indicate it is a yes/no question, and the hinge mark () denotes that the S handshape digit () makes a nodding motion.
[src:sign-language/aslwrite] The circular point at the end is a full stop mark indicating the end of the sentence.
[src:sign-language/aslwrite] Unlike in English writing, the full stop mark () is employed for all sentences, even questions (as seen here).
[src:sign-language/aslwrite] Breaks in the sentence, as seen below, are denoted by the shoulder shift mark ().
[src:sign-language/aslwrite] The text on the right is from Chapters 1:2–4 of the Book of Ruth.
[src:sign-language/aslwrite] The first quoted text is the verse in English and the second is an ASL gloss.
[src:sign-language/aslwrite] Due to the complexity of the writing system and its need for flexibility for movements, it means that producing anything in a digital format is difficult.
[src:sign-language/aslwrite] However, there are efforts to create fonts headed by members of its Facebook group, notably looking at proper font creation and using current keyboard characters such as ' } ' or ' _.
[src:sign-language/aslwrite] ' to achieve minor forms of communication in ASL over text.
[src:sign-language/aslwrite] An example phrase is " }_.U- " which means 'thank you' in ASL.
[src:sign-language/at-t-corporation] During the Bell System, AT&T was at times the world's largest telecommunications company, the world's largest cable television operator, and a regulated monopoly.
[src:sign-language/at-t-corporation] At its peak in the 1950s and 1960s, it employed one million people and its revenue ranged between US$3 billion in 1950 ($43.6 billion in present-day terms) and $12 billion in 1966 ($123 billion in present-day terms).
[src:sign-language/at-t-corporation] In 2005, AT&T was acquired by "Baby Bell" and former subsidiary SBC Communications for more than $16 billion ($26.4 billion in present-day terms).
[src:sign-language/at-t-corporation] SBC then changed its name to AT&T Inc., with AT&T Corporation continuing to exist as a long-distance calling subsidiary until its dissolution on May 1, 2024.
[src:sign-language/at-t-corporation] AT&T started with Bell Patent Association, a legal entity established in 1874 to protect the patent rights of Alexander Graham Bell after he invented the telephone system.
[src:sign-language/at-t-corporation] Originally a verbal agreement, it was formalized in writing in 1875 as Bell Telephone Company.
[src:sign-language/at-t-corporation] In 1880 the management of American Bell created what would become **AT&T Long Lines**.
[src:sign-language/at-t-corporation] The project was the first of its kind to create a nationwide long-distance network with a commercially viable cost-structure.
[src:sign-language/at-t-corporation] The project was formally incorporated in New York as a separate company named **American Telephone and Telegraph Company** on March 3, 1885.
[src:sign-language/at-t-corporation] Originating in New York City, its long-distance telephone network reached Chicago, Illinois, in 1892, with its multitudes of local exchanges continuing to stretch further and further yearly, eventually creating a continent-wide telephone system.
[src:sign-language/at-t-corporation] With this assets transfer at the very end of the 19th century, AT&T became the parent of both American Bell and the Bell System.
[src:sign-language/at-t-corporation] On April 30, 1907, Theodore Newton Vail became president of AT&T.
[src:sign-language/at-t-corporation] Vail believed in the superiority of one phone system and AT&T adopted the slogan "One Policy, One System, Universal Service." This would be the company's philosophy for the next 70 years.
[src:sign-language/at-t-corporation] Under Vail, AT&T began buying up many of the smaller telephone companies including Western Union telegraph.
[src:sign-language/at-t-corporation] These actions brought unwanted attention from antitrust regulators.
[src:sign-language/at-t-corporation] Anxious to avoid action from government antitrust suits, AT&T and the federal government entered into an agreement known as the Kingsbury Commitment.
[src:sign-language/at-t-corporation] In the Kingsbury Commitment, AT&T and the government reached an agreement that allowed AT&T to continue operating as a telephone monopoly, subject to certain conditions, including divesting its interest in Western Union.
[src:sign-language/at-t-corporation] While AT&T periodically faced scrutiny from regulators, this state of affairs continued until the company's breakup in 1984.
[src:sign-language/at-t-corporation] Throughout most of the 20th century, AT&T held a semi-monopoly on phone service in the United States and Canada through a network of companies called the Bell System.
[src:sign-language/at-t-corporation] At this time, the company was nicknamed **Ma Bell**.
[src:sign-language/at-t-corporation] AT&T closely monitored new telephony technologies, although initially for private communication.
[src:sign-language/at-t-corporation] In 1906, it sent observers to Reginald Fessenden's radiotelephone demonstration of his alternator transmitter.
[src:sign-language/at-t-corporation] Fessenden hoped that AT&T would purchase his company and patents, but the phone company concluded that Fessenden's system was not sufficiently refined.
[src:sign-language/at-t-corporation] It was not until the development of vacuum-tube transmitters that radiotelephony became practical.
[src:sign-language/at-t-corporation] AT&T purchased the commercial rights to Lee de Forest's vacuum-tube and radio patents.
[src:sign-language/at-t-corporation] In 1919, the Radio Corporation of America (RCA) was formed, from the assets of the American subsidiary of the Marconi Company.
[src:sign-language/at-t-corporation] A series of patent cross-licensing agreements were made, including, effective July 1, 1920, one between RCA's founders and AT&T, which granted AT&T exclusive rights within the United States for "Public Service Telephony".
[src:sign-language/at-t-corporation] In 1920, a telephone link using radio transmissions was established between Avalon Island, California and the mainland, although this was later replaced by an underwater cable, because local amateurs began to amuse themselves by listening-in to private conversations.
[src:sign-language/at-t-corporation] It was recognized that a potential use of unrestricted radio transmissions was broadcasting to a widespread audience.
[src:sign-language/at-t-corporation] In a 1919 presentation at the Convention of the American Institute of Electrical Engineers, two company engineers noted the possibility for "the broadcasting of news, time and weather signals, and warning.
[src:sign-language/at-t-corporation] In some cases one objection to radio-telephony would be an advantage in this class of service." The Westinghouse Electric and Manufacturing Company later purchased the successor company to Fessenden's early work.
[src:sign-language/at-t-corporation] Employing vacuum-tube transmitters, it inaugurated well-financed radio broadcasting stations, starting in November 1920 with KDKA, located at its East Pittsburgh, Pennsylvania headquarters, and soon many additional stations began operating.
[src:sign-language/at-t-corporation] In December 1921, AT&T longline engineers John F.
[src:sign-language/at-t-corporation] Lauderback prepared a memo reviewing AT&T's radio broadcasting options.
[src:sign-language/at-t-corporation] They stated that commercial broadcasting was a significant opportunity, and proposed the nationwide establishment of 38 stations, linked together by long-distance telephone lines, that could be hired out (known, using telephone terminology, as "toll stations").
[src:sign-language/at-t-corporation] Radio broadcasting in the United States dramatically expanded in 1922, with over 500 stations by the end of the year.
[src:sign-language/at-t-corporation] Thus, AT&T ended up establishing only two stations: WBAY (later WEAF) in New York City, and WCAP in Washington, D.C., licensed to its Chesapeake and Potomac subsidiary.
[src:sign-language/at-t-corporation] WEAF was the company's showcase station.
[src:sign-language/at-t-corporation] Its primary competition was RCA's WJZ, also in New York City, although, based on AT&T's interpretation of the cross-licensing agreements, WJZ was prohibited from commercial operation.
[src:sign-language/at-t-corporation] Moreover, WJZ's engineer-in-charge, Carl Dreher, later admitted that "WEAF... was better on the technical end than we were...
[src:sign-language/at-t-corporation] Raymond Guy... sums it up in his reminiscences...
[src:sign-language/at-t-corporation] 'AT&T did things with a more thorough knowledge of what they were doing...
[src:sign-language/at-t-corporation] They just knew more about telephony than we did, as you might expect.
[src:sign-language/at-t-corporation] They had the best telephone engineers in the world.
[src:sign-language/at-t-corporation] AT&T initially found that, instead of hiring WEAF, most potential broadcasters wanted to establish their own stations.
[src:sign-language/at-t-corporation] According to AT&T's interpretation of the RCA cross-licensing agreements, its Western Electric subsidiary had the exclusive right to manufacture and sell radio transmitters, although most early stations had built their own.
[src:sign-language/at-t-corporation] In 1924, with only about 50 of the more than 500 U.S. stations having Western Electric transmitters, AT&T started to move aggressively to enforce its patent rights, and began a court case charging infringement against WHN, a New York City-area station.
[src:sign-language/at-t-corporation] Thayer issued a statement that "We have no desire for a monopoly of the air", this was met with widespread skepticism, as earlier sales contracts for Western Electric transmitters had included a clause prohibiting stations "to operate for hire".
[src:sign-language/at-t-corporation] This restriction on commercial programming was seen as a covert way to largely eliminate competition, as it was becoming apparent that for most stations there was no way to finance operations without selling airtime.
[src:sign-language/at-t-corporation] In view of these concerns, Commerce secretary Herbert Hoover issued a statement that "neither will our public policy allow [radio broadcasting] to become monpolized".
[src:sign-language/at-t-corporation] WHN paid $2,000 for a personal, non-transferable license to do general telephonic broadcasting, including for toll or hire, for the entire term of the patents.
[src:sign-language/at-t-corporation] Even this was too much for some stations, including KFAY in Medford, Oregon, which was unable to afford a license fee of $500, as well as two Portland, Oregon stations, KGG and KFOH.
[src:sign-language/at-t-corporation] However, despite earlier concerns, the agreement allowed stations to begin commercial operation.
[src:sign-language/at-t-corporation] Meanwhile, AT&T engineers worked to develop a network of radio stations, linked by specially prepared long-distance telephone lines.
[src:sign-language/at-t-corporation] The first permanent link, originating at WEAF, was established in the summer of 1923, to station WMAF in South Dartmouth, Massachusetts.
[src:sign-language/at-t-corporation] As it expanded, this network became known as the "WEAF chain".
[src:sign-language/at-t-corporation] AT&T's BCA consolidation allowed for two possible outcomes: if AT&T decided to withdraw from broadcasting, then the transfer of its radio operations would be simplified, otherwise, the new entity could continue to be run semi-independently of the parent corporation.
[src:sign-language/at-t-corporation] During BCA's short existence, the standard WEAF chain consisted of a network of 17 stations, concentrated in the northeastern United States, but also extended westward to WDAF in Kansas City, Missouri.
[src:sign-language/at-t-corporation] Individual evening hourly station rates ranged from $170 for three stations located in smaller communities to $480 for flagship WEAF.
[src:sign-language/at-t-corporation] The standard charge for an hour of evening programming over the entire roster of stations was $4,080, before any applicable discounts.
[src:sign-language/at-t-corporation] Unpublicized when the BCA subsidiary was established were ongoing intense negotiations between AT&T and the "radio group" companies, led by RCA, about the status of the cross-licensing agreements, and the overall future of the broadcasting industry.
[src:sign-language/at-t-corporation] On July 21, AT&T issued a press release announcing BCA's sale to RCA for $1,000,000, which in turn used these assets to form the National Broadcasting Company.
[src:sign-language/at-t-corporation] This memo stated that although operation of WEAF and the WEAF chain had been financially successful, it had been concluded that "while the technical principle was similar to that of the telephone system, the objective of the broadcasting station was quite different from that of a telephone system.
[src:sign-language/at-t-corporation] AT&T had a domestic and global presence in laying the infrastructure of undersea routes for telecommunications.
[src:sign-language/at-t-corporation] Navy commissioned a network of undersea surveillance cables for foreign submarine detection.
[src:sign-language/at-t-corporation] AT&T was probably, according to internal employees, involved in this Sound Surveillance System (SOSUS).
[src:sign-language/at-t-corporation] After completion, AT&T began commercial operations in cable laying for communications in 1955.
[src:sign-language/at-t-corporation] The implementation of cables assured local and long-distance telephone or data services would provide revenue for the company.
[src:sign-language/at-t-corporation] AT&T Long Lines was one of the divisions responsible for the cable-laying and maintaining of Long Lines' undersea cables.
[src:sign-language/at-t-corporation] Western Electric was the manufacturing company responsible for production and supply of undersea coaxial equipment and later, fiber cables.
[src:sign-language/at-t-corporation] Equipment such as repeaters was manufactured in Clark, New Jersey and coaxial cable was manufactured in Baltimore, Maryland .
[src:sign-language/at-t-corporation] Also, Bell Labs was responsible for the innovations of products or technologies in cabling in transmission by undersea systems.
[src:sign-language/at-t-corporation] In 1955, the first trans-Atlantic telephone undersea cable, TAT-1, from North America to Europe was installed by AT&T.
[src:sign-language/at-t-corporation] This installation allowed 48 telephone circuits to be used for long-distance calling.
[src:sign-language/at-t-corporation] When partnering with other global Telecommunications companies, such as the French Cables de Lyon and German Felten & Guilleaume, Bell Labs provided the specification and inspection of non Bell System cable for networks such as the TAT-2.
[src:sign-language/at-t-corporation] By the continuous undersea network installations, AT&T was a globally technology leader with the 1970 installed TAT-5 and the 1975 installed TAT-6, achieving 720 channels and then 4000 channels for transmitting voice or data.
[src:sign-language/at-t-corporation] Prior to 1963, AT&T had to charter oceanic ships, such as the CS Monarch (1945) for installations.
[src:sign-language/at-t-corporation] AT&T purchased *CS Long Lines* in 1961 and operated it with several cable laying ships that would provide, either the laying or repair of cabling under the subsidiary, Transoceanic Cable Ship Company.
[src:sign-language/at-t-corporation] After the break-up, AT&T operated their ships under a subsidiary called AT&T Submarine Systems Inc, based in Morristown, New Jersey, until they sold six ships to Tyco International Ltd in 1997 for $850 million.
[src:sign-language/at-t-corporation] AT&T continued to maintain their communication building facilities.
[src:sign-language/at-t-corporation] Between 1951 and 2000, AT&T was listed 73 times in cable laying operations for specific routes deployed.
[src:sign-language/at-t-corporation] The Cable Ship *Long Lines* had 23 cable runs from 1963 to 1992, with the first deep-sea trial of optical fiber cable in 1982 leading to the consortium of countries and locations for the TAT-8 fiber cable implementation of 1988.
[src:sign-language/at-t-corporation] The United States Justice Department opened the case *United States v.
[src:sign-language/at-t-corporation] This was prompted by suspicion that AT&T was using monopoly profits from its Western Electric subsidiary to subsidize the cost of its network, a violation of antitrust law.
[src:sign-language/at-t-corporation] A settlement to this case was finalized in 1982, leading to the division of the company on January 1, 1984, into seven Regional Bell Operating Companies, commonly known as Baby Bells.
[src:sign-language/at-t-corporation] Post-breakup, the former parent company's main business was now AT&T Communications Inc., which focused on long-distance services, and with other non-RBOC activities.
[src:sign-language/at-t-corporation] AT&T announced in 1995 that it would split into three companies: a manufacturing/R&D company, a computer company, and a services company.
[src:sign-language/at-t-corporation] NCR, Bell Labs and AT&T Technologies were to be spun off by 1997.
[src:sign-language/at-t-corporation] In preparation for its spin-off, AT&T Technologies was now Lucent Technologies.
[src:sign-language/at-t-corporation] Lucent was completely spun off from AT&T in 1996.
[src:sign-language/at-t-corporation] On January 31, 2005, the "Baby Bell" company SBC Communications announced its plans to acquire "Ma Bell" AT&T Corp. for $16 billion.
[src:sign-language/at-t-corporation] SBC announced in October 2005 that it would shed the "SBC" brand and take the more recognizable AT&T brand, along with the old AT&T's "T" NYSE ticker symbol.
[src:sign-language/at-t-corporation] Merger approval concluded on November 18, 2005; SBC Communications began rebranding the following Monday, November 21 as "the new AT&T" and began trading under the "T" symbol on December 1.
[src:sign-language/at-t-corporation] Present-day AT&T Inc. claims AT&T Corp.'s history as its own, but retains SBC's pre-2005 stock price history and corporate structure.
[src:sign-language/at-t-corporation] As well, all SEC filings before 2005 are under SBC, not AT&T.
[src:sign-language/at-t-corporation] From 1885 to 1910, AT&T was headquartered at 125 Milk Street in Boston.
[src:sign-language/at-t-corporation] With its expansion it moved to New York City, to a headquarters on 195 Broadway (close to what is now the World Trade Center site).
[src:sign-language/at-t-corporation] The property originally belonged to Western Union, of which AT&T held a controlling interest until 1913 when AT&T divested its interest as part of the Kingsbury Commitment.
[src:sign-language/at-t-corporation] Construction of the current building began in 1912.
[src:sign-language/at-t-corporation] The lobby of the AT&T Building was one of the most unusual ones of the era.
[src:sign-language/at-t-corporation] Instead of a large double-high space, similar to the nearby Woolworth Building, Bosworth designed what is called a "hypostyle hall", with full-bodied Doric columns modeled on the Parthenon, marking out a grid.
[src:sign-language/at-t-corporation] Bosworth was seeking to coordinate the classical tradition with the requirements of a modern building.
[src:sign-language/at-t-corporation] Columns were not merely the decorative elements they had become in the hands of other architects but created all the illusion of being real supports.
[src:sign-language/at-t-corporation] Bosworth also designed the campus of MIT as well as Theodore N.
[src:sign-language/at-t-corporation] Vail's mansion in Morristown, New Jersey.
[src:sign-language/at-t-corporation] In 1978, AT&T commissioned a new building at 550 Madison Avenue.
[src:sign-language/at-t-corporation] This new AT&T Building was designed by Philip Johnson and quickly became an icon of the new Postmodern architectural style.
[src:sign-language/at-t-corporation] The building was completed in 1984, the very year of the divestiture of the Bell System.
[src:sign-language/at-t-corporation] The building proved to be too large for the post-divestiture corporation and in 1993, AT&T leased the building to Sony, who then subsequently owned the building until it was sold in 2013.
[src:sign-language/at-t-corporation] In 1969, AT&T began plans to construct an administration corporate complex in the suburbs.
[src:sign-language/at-t-corporation] In early 1970, AT&T began purchases of land in the suburbs of New Jersey for this office complex and began construction in 1974.
[src:sign-language/at-t-corporation] The 295 North Maple Avenue and Interstate 287 location of Basking Ridge in Bernards Township, New Jersey was completed in 1975 for the AT&T General Department offices.
[src:sign-language/at-t-corporation] Employees began moving, in November 1975, to the seven inter-connected building complex using 28 acre of the property.
[src:sign-language/at-t-corporation] The property had a 15-acre underground parking garage with spaces for 3,900 vehicles, and included a Class 1 licensed private helipad, a two-story cafeteria, a wood-burning fireplace, an indoor waterfall at the entrance lobby, and a seven-acre created lake for flood control.
[src:sign-language/at-t-corporation] The entire property was 130 acre and cost $219 million to construct.
[src:sign-language/at-t-corporation] Later, across the street from the complex, AT&T purchased additional land and established its Learning Center in 1985, at 300 North Maple Avenue, to become a 171 conference room inn.
[src:sign-language/at-t-corporation] The AT&T Learning Center won the commercial property known as Somerset County's Land Development Award that year.
[src:sign-language/at-t-corporation] In 1992, Basking Ridge location would become a corporate headquarters just before AT&T leased the New York City, 550 Madison Avenue building to Sony in 1993.
[src:sign-language/at-t-corporation] The corporate statue, known as "Golden Boy" was moved in 1992, from the former New York City headquarters to this current New Jersey headquarters.
[src:sign-language/at-t-corporation] In 1992, a corporate art consultant approached, artist sculptor, Elyn Zimmerman, to commission a 30-foot diameter project with fountain and seating area for the conference center courtyard gardens.
[src:sign-language/at-t-corporation] In 1994, the project was completed and had one 34 ton granite boulder centered on top of the other boulders, which flowed water from the fountain designed by fountain engineer, Dr.
[src:sign-language/at-t-corporation] AT&T occupancy at the location peaked to 6,000 employees in its heyday before AT&T experienced competition and downsizing.
[src:sign-language/at-t-corporation] In October 2001, the Basking Ridge property was 140 acre with 2.6 million square feet and was placed for sale.
[src:sign-language/at-t-corporation] Basking Ridge employee occupancy, prior to the sale were approximately 3,200 employees.
[src:sign-language/at-t-corporation] In April 2002, Pharmacia Corporation purchased the complex for $210 million for their corporate headquarters from existing Peapack-Gladstone, New Jersey headquarters.
[src:sign-language/at-t-corporation] A short time afterwards, in 2005, Verizon purchased the former complex, excluding the hotel/conference room building, from Pfizer for Verizon Wireless Headquarters and consolidation of employees from Manhattan as well as other nearby New Jersey building locations.
[src:sign-language/at-t-corporation] In 2007, Pfizer placed the North Maple Inn for sale.
[src:sign-language/at-t-corporation] At the time, it was a four-diamond, certified hotel and conference center under IACC ("International Association of Conference Centers") designation.
[src:sign-language/at-t-corporation] In 2015, Verizon performed a sale-leaseback agreement valued at $650.3 million on the complex with the address previously known as One Verizon Way.
[src:sign-language/at-t-corporation] In 2017, the 35 acre hotel/conference center was known as the Dolce Basking Ridge Hotel and sold for $30 million.
[src:sign-language/at-t-corporation] On February 15, 2024, AT&T Inc. filed notice with the Kentucky Public Service Commission that it intends to make an internal structural change and merge AT&T Corp. into AT&T Enterprises, Inc., which will become a limited liability company.
[src:sign-language/at-t-corporation] In a filing with the South Dakota Secretary of State dated January 30, 2024, the reason given for the merger is that New York state law does not allow AT&T Corp. to be directly converted into an LLC.
[src:sign-language/at-t-corporation] Although acquired by SBC in 2005, AT&T Corp. has remained a separate entity within the corporate structure of AT&T Inc.
[src:sign-language/at-t-corporation] The merger, said to create "greater operational efficiencies", will end the existence of the nearly 140-year-old entity.
[src:sign-language/at-t-corporation] The internal merger took effect on May 1, 2024.
[src:sign-language/at-t-corporation] AT&T Communications was renamed **AT&T Communications – East, Inc.** and sold long-distance telephone service and operated as a CLEC outside of the borders of the Bell Operating Companies that AT&T owned.
[src:sign-language/at-t-corporation] It has now been absorbed into AT&T Corp. and all but 4 of the original 22 subsidiaries that formed AT&T Communications continue to exist.
[src:sign-language/at-t-corporation] AT&T Laboratories has been integrated into AT&T Labs, formerly named SBC Laboratories.
[src:sign-language/at-t-corporation] AT&T was formerly known as "Ma Bell" and affectionately called "Mother" by phone phreaks.
[src:sign-language/at-t-corporation] During some strikes by its employees, picketers would wear T-shirts reading, "Ma Bell is a real mother." Before the break-up, there was greater consumer recognition of the "Bell System" name, in comparison to the name AT&T.
[src:sign-language/at-t-corporation] This prompted the company to launch an advertising campaign after the break-up to increase its name recognition.
[src:sign-language/at-t-corporation] Spinoffs like the Regional Bell Operating Companies or *RBOC*s were often called "Baby Bells".
[src:sign-language/at-t-corporation] Ironically, "Ma Bell" was acquired by one of its "Baby Bells", SBC Communications, in 2005.
[src:sign-language/at-t-corporation] The AT&T Globe Symbol, the corporate logo designed by Saul Bass in 1983 and originally used by AT&T Information Systems, was created because part of the *United States v.
[src:sign-language/at-t-corporation] AT&T* settlement required AT&T to relinquish all claims to the use of Bell System trademarks.
[src:sign-language/at-t-corporation] It has been nicknamed the "Death Star" in reference to the Death Star space station in *Star Wars* which the logo resembles.
[src:sign-language/at-t-corporation] In 1999 it was changed from the 12-line design to the 8-line design.
[src:sign-language/at-t-corporation] Again in 2005 it was changed to the 3D transparent "marble" design created by Interbrand for use by the parent company AT&T Inc.
[src:sign-language/at-t-corporation] The following is a list of the 16 CEOs of AT&T Corporation, from its incorporation in 1885 until its purchase by SBC Communications in 2005.
[src:sign-language/sign-language-p01] Wherever communities of deaf and hard of hearing people exist, sign languages have developed as a means of communication and form the core of local Deaf cultures.
[src:sign-language/sign-language-p01] Although signing is used primarily by deaf and hard of hearing people, it is also used by hearing individuals, such as those with deaf family members including children of deaf adults (CODAs).
[src:sign-language/sign-language-p01] Sign languages are distinct from body language, a type of nonverbal communication.
[src:sign-language/sign-language-p01] Linguists also distinguish natural sign languages from other systems that are precursors to them or derived from them, such as constructed manual codes for spoken languages, home sign, baby sign language, and signs used with non-human primates.
[src:sign-language/sign-language-p01] The number of sign languages worldwide is not precisely known.
[src:sign-language/sign-language-p01] Each country generally has its own native sign language, and some have more than one.
[src:sign-language/sign-language-p01] The 2021 edition of *Ethnologue* lists 150 sign languages, while the SIGN-HUB Atlas of Sign Language Structures lists over 200 and notes that there are more that have not yet been documented.
[src:sign-language/sign-language-p01] As of 2021, Indo-Pakistani Sign Language is the most widely used sign language in the world, and *Ethnologue* ranks it as the 151st most "spoken" language in the world.
[src:sign-language/sign-language-p01] Some sign languages have obtained some form of legal recognition.
[src:sign-language/sign-language-p01] Groups of deaf people have used sign languages throughout history.
[src:sign-language/sign-language-p01] Debate around European monastic sign languages developed in the Middle Ages has come to regard them as gestural systems rather than true sign languages.
[src:sign-language/sign-language-p01] Monastic sign languages were the basis for the first known manual alphabet used in deaf schools, developed by Pedro Ponce de León.
[src:sign-language/sign-language-p01] The earliest records of contact between Europeans and Indigenous peoples of the Gulf Coast region in what is now Texas and northern Mexico note a fully formed sign language already in use by the time of the Europeans' arrival there.
[src:sign-language/sign-language-p01] These records include the accounts of Cabeza de Vaca in 1527 and Coronado in 1541.
[src:sign-language/sign-language-p01] In 1620, Juan Pablo Bonet published *Reducción de las letras y arte para enseñar a hablar a los mudos* ('Reduction of letters and art for teaching mute people to speak') in Madrid.
[src:sign-language/sign-language-p01] It is considered the first modern treatise of sign language phonetics, setting out a method of oral education for deaf people and a manual alphabet.
[src:sign-language/sign-language-p01] In Britain, manual alphabets were also in use for a number of purposes, such as secret communication, public speaking, or communication by or with deaf people.
[src:sign-language/sign-language-p01] In 1648, John Bulwer described "Master Babington", a deaf man proficient in the use of a manual alphabet, "contryved on the joynts of his fingers", whose wife could converse with him easily, even in the dark through the use of tactile signing.
[src:sign-language/sign-language-p01] In 1680, George Dalgarno published *Didascalocophus, or, The deaf and dumb mans tutor*, in which he presented his own method of deaf education, including an "arthrological" alphabet, where letters are indicated by pointing to different joints of the fingers and palm of the left hand.
[src:sign-language/sign-language-p01] Arthrological systems had been in use by hearing people for some time; some have speculated that they can be traced to early Ogham manual alphabets.
[src:sign-language/sign-language-p01] The vowels of this alphabet have survived in the modern alphabets used in British Sign Language, Auslan and New Zealand Sign Language.
[src:sign-language/sign-language-p01] The earliest known printed pictures of consonants of the modern two-handed alphabet appeared in 1698 with *Digiti Lingua* (Latin for *Language* [or *Tongue*] *of the Finger*), a pamphlet by an anonymous author who was himself unable to speak.
[src:sign-language/sign-language-p01] He suggested that the manual alphabet could also be used by mutes, for silence and secrecy, or purely for entertainment.
[src:sign-language/sign-language-p01] Nine of its letters can be traced to earlier alphabets, and 17 letters of the modern two-handed alphabet can be found among the two sets of 26 handshapes depicted.
[src:sign-language/sign-language-p01] Charles de La Fin published a book in 1692 describing an alphabetic system where pointing to a body part represented the first letter of the part (e.g.
[src:sign-language/sign-language-p01] Brow=B), and vowels were located on the fingertips as with the other British systems.
[src:sign-language/sign-language-p01] He described such codes for both English and Latin.
[src:sign-language/sign-language-p01] By 1720, the British manual alphabet had found more or less its present form.
[src:sign-language/sign-language-p01] During the Polygar Wars against the British, Veeran Sundaralingam communicated with Veerapandiya Kattabomman's mute younger brother, Oomaithurai, by using their own sign language.
[src:sign-language/sign-language-p01] Frenchman Charles-Michel de l'Épée published his manual alphabet in the 18th century, which has survived largely unchanged in France and North America until the present time.
[src:sign-language/sign-language-p01] In 1755, Abbé de l'Épée founded the first school for deaf children in Paris; Laurent Clerc was arguably its most famous graduate.
[src:sign-language/sign-language-p01] Clerc went to the United States with Thomas Hopkins Gallaudet to found the American School for the Deaf in Hartford, Connecticut, in 1817.
[src:sign-language/sign-language-p01] Gallaudet's son, Edward Miner Gallaudet, founded a school for the deaf in 1857 in Washington, D.C., which in 1864 became the National Deaf-Mute College.
[src:sign-language/sign-language-p01] Now called Gallaudet University, it is still the only liberal arts university for deaf people in the world.
[src:sign-language/sign-language-p01] International Sign, formerly known as Gestuno, is used mainly at international deaf events such as the Deaflympics and meetings of the World Federation of the Deaf.
[src:sign-language/sign-language-p01] While recent studies claim that International Sign is a kind of a pidgin, they conclude that it is more complex than a typical pidgin and indeed is more like a full sign language.
[src:sign-language/sign-language-p01] Sign languages have capability and complexity equal to spoken languages; their study as part of the field of linguistics has demonstrated that they exhibit the fundamental properties that exist in all languages.
[src:sign-language/sign-language-p01] Such fundamental properties include duality of patterning and recursion.
[src:sign-language/sign-language-p01] Duality of patterning means that languages are composed of smaller, meaningless units which can be combined into larger units with meaning (see below).
[src:sign-language/sign-language-p01] The term recursion means that languages exhibit grammatical rules and the output of such a rule can be the input of the same rule.
